update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Liberal IV fluid for all postop"},{"label":"B","text":"Postoperative fluid management — goal-directed restrictive trend"},{"label":"C","text":"No fluid management needed"},{"label":"D","text":"TPN for all postop"},{"label":"E","text":"Fluid restriction always"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Postoperative fluid management — goal-directed restrictive trend**: (1) **Fluid types**: - **Crystalloid**: balanced solutions (Lactated Ringer''s, Plasma-Lyte) preferred over 0.9% NSS for resuscitation (avoid hyperchloremic acidosis); 5% dextrose for hypoglycemia adjunct; - **Colloid**: albumin (5% for resuscitation in selected — septic shock per Surviving Sepsis 2021); HES (hydroxyethyl starch) no longer recommended (renal injury + mortality); gelatins; - **Blood products** for specific indications; (2) **Goal-directed fluid therapy (GDT)**: - Avoid both over-resuscitation (third spacing, edema, ileus, anastomotic, ARDS) AND under-resuscitation (organ hypoperfusion); - Dynamic measures of fluid responsiveness: passive leg raise (PLR), pulse pressure variation (PPV), stroke volume variation (SVV), POCUS; - CVP no longer recommended as fluid responsiveness predictor; - Targets: MAP > 65, lactate clearance, UO 0.5 mL/kg/hr (caution in over-resuscitating just to UO); (3) **ERAS principles** for fluid: - Pre-op: no prolonged NPO (clear fluid up to 2h), carb loading 2h pre-op (improves insulin sensitivity); - Intra-op: balanced solutions, restrictive but adequate; avoid ''over-the-top'' fluid; - Post-op: oral intake as soon as tolerated; minimize maintenance IV; goal euvolemia; (4) **RELIEF trial (Myles NEJM 2018)** — restrictive (low) vs liberal (higher) fluid in major abdominal surgery: restrictive associated with more AKI; modern recommendation: moderate (not extreme either way) goal-directed; (5) **Electrolyte management postop**: - **Sodium**: monitor; both hyponatremia (overhydration with hypotonic) + hypernatremia possible - **Potassium**: monitor; K losses from NG, diarrhea, diuretic, alkalosis; replete carefully (max 10 mEq/h peripheral, 20 mEq/h central with monitoring) - **Magnesium**: often low postop; replete (Mg essential for K + Ca regulation, neuromuscular, cardiac) - **Calcium**: hypocalcemia post-thyroid/parathyroid surgery; transfusion (citrate); replete - **Phosphate**: refeeding syndrome, depletion; (6) **Glycemic control**: target 140-180 (avoid both extreme hyper + hypoglycemia); insulin sliding scale + correction; long-acting basal + bolus for outpatient regimens; (7) **Acid-base disorders postop**: - Metabolic acidosis: lactate (perfusion), hyperchloremia (NSS over-use), ketone (NPO, DKA) - Metabolic alkalosis: NG suction, vomiting, diuretic - Respiratory: hypoventilation (opioid, pain, sedation), hyperventilation (anxiety, pain, sepsis); (8) **Special situations**: - Cardiac surgery — pulmonary edema risk - Major liver resection — coagulopathy, hypoalbumin, ascites - Bariatric — dumping, dehydration - Sepsis — initial resuscitation 30 mL/kg crystalloid then goal-directed; (9) **Monitoring**: weight daily (most accurate volume change), I/O, electrolytes daily or more, hemodynamics, end-organ perfusion (UO, lactate, mental status)

---

**Perioperative fluid + electrolyte management** — fundamental + has evolved significantly. Major shift from ''liberal'' to ''restrictive moderate'' (goal-directed). **Crystalloid selection**: - **Balanced (LR, Plasma-Lyte)** preferred over **0.9% NaCl** (normal saline) for resuscitation - NS large volumes → hyperchloremic acidosis, AKI risk (SMART, SALT-ED trials) - LR contains some K (4 mEq/L) — caution in hyperkalemia; safe in most - D5W for hypoglycemia/hypernatremia adjunct **Colloid use**: - **Albumin** — selected (e.g., large volume paracentesis, hepatorenal syndrome, septic shock per Surviving Sepsis; no general benefit over crystalloid per SAFE trial) - **HES (hydroxyethyl starch)** — NOT recommended (CHEST, 6S trials — increased renal injury + mortality) - **Gelatins** — limited use, expensive, no superior outcomes **Goal-directed therapy**: avoid both extremes; dynamic measures preferred over static (CVP, urine output alone). **ERAS fluid principles**: - No prolonged NPO (clear fluid up to 2h) - Carb loading 2h pre-op - Moderate intraoperative (balanced solutions) - Early oral intake postop - Minimize maintenance IV when oral OK **Restrictive vs liberal** — RELIEF trial (Myles NEJM 2018): restrictive fluid in major abdominal surgery associated with more AKI vs slightly liberal; modern consensus: moderate goal-directed (not extreme either way). **Electrolyte considerations postop**: - Na: monitor; hyponatremia from hypotonic fluid + SIADH common postop; hypernatremia from dehydration - K: NG losses, diuretic; replete carefully - Mg: low common; impacts K + Ca + cardiac; replete IV - Ca: post-thyroid/parathyroid; transfusion (citrate) - PO4: refeeding syndrome **Refeeding syndrome**: severely malnourished resuming feeds → PO4 + Mg + K drop into cells; cardiac + neuromuscular dysfunction; thiamine deficiency manifests. Prevent: gradual feed advancement + thiamine pre-feed + electrolyte monitoring + replacement. **Acid-base**: assess Anion Gap; common postop disorders: metabolic acidosis (lactic, hyperchloremic), metabolic alkalosis (NG, vomiting), respiratory acidosis (hypoventilation). **Glycemic**: target 140-180; hyperglycemia + hypoglycemia both bad; use insulin sliding scale + correction. **Special**: cardiac surgery (pulmonary edema risk; restrictive); liver resection (coagulopathy, ascites, hypoalbumin); bariatric (dumping, dehydration risk).'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'Basic science: fluid + electrolyte management

คำถาม: postoperative IV fluid + electrolyte management';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Standard ACLS only"},{"label":"B","text":"Cardiac Arrest after Cardiac Surgery (CALS) Protocol — modified ACLS"},{"label":"C","text":"Do not perform CPR"},{"label":"D","text":"Use general anesthesia for resuscitation"},{"label":"E","text":"Wait for cardiologist"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Cardiac Arrest after Cardiac Surgery (CALS) Protocol — modified ACLS**: (1) **Critical differences from standard ACLS**: - Recent thoracotomy + sternotomy + intracardiac/great vessel anatomy - Resternotomy with internal cardiac massage if external CPR fails - Specific arrest etiologies — VF, tamponade, bleeding, ischemia, hypovolemia, pacemaker; (2) **Immediate response within 5 minutes** (modified ACLS): - Confirm arrest - Call for help + arrest team + perfusionist (CPB on standby) - Begin chest compressions (caution with sternotomy site / wires) - Defibrillate VF/VT (3 shocks before drug if witnessed in monitored ICU) - Pacing if asystole / bradycardia + pacemaker available (post-op patients often have epicardial wires); (3) **Specific etiologic management**: - **Tamponade** — open chest within 5 min if PEA / ineffective CPR (life-saving) - **Hemorrhage** — open chest, identify + control source, transfuse - **Tension pneumothorax** — decompress - **Hypovolemia** — fluid + blood - **Hyperkalemia** — Ca + insulin + glucose - **MI / graft thrombosis** — emergent intervention; (4) **Resternotomy**: - Indications: VF/VT unresponsive 3 shocks, PEA without reversible cause, asystole, suspected tamponade - Within 5 min of arrest to maximize survival - Internal cardiac massage 100/min, defibrillation internal, identify cause - All ICUs caring for post-cardiac surgery patients should have resternotomy capability; (5) **Drugs in CALS**: - Avoid epinephrine bolus initially (can cause severe HTN + intracardiac complications) - Use vasopressin / norepi infusion - Amiodarone, lidocaine for VF/VT; (6) **Extracorporeal life support (ECMO / ECLS)**: - VA-ECMO bridge for refractory - Cannulation femoral + peripheral or central - Improved outcomes with rapid deployment; (7) **Outcomes** with CALS protocol — survival higher (50%+) than standard ACLS in cardiac surgery patients due to addressing surgical etiology + resternotomy; (8) **Training + drills** — STS CALS course + simulation; ICU + OR teams should be familiar; (9) **Documentation + debrief**: M&M, learnings, prevention; family communication

---

**Cardiac Arrest after Cardiac Surgery (CALS)** — distinct protocol per Society of Thoracic Surgeons (STS) due to unique pathophysiology + therapeutic opportunities. **Why different from standard ACLS**: - Specific etiologies (tamponade 35%, hemorrhage 25%, VF/VT 25%, MI/graft, tension pneumothorax, hyperkalemia, pacemaker failure) - Recent thoracotomy + sternotomy enables internal cardiac massage + visualization - Standard chest compressions may injure surgical site - Epicardial pacing wires often available - Goal: identify + treat specific cause within 5 min to optimize outcome **Key steps (STS CALS Protocol)**: 1. Within 1 min: confirm arrest, call for help (arrest team + perfusion) 2. VF/VT (witnessed monitored ICU): 3 shocks immediately, then chest compressions 3. Asystole / severe bradycardia: pace with epicardial wires if available 4. PEA: think of reversible causes (tamponade, tension pneumothorax, hypovolemia, hyperkalemia) 5. **Resternotomy within 5 min** if: - VF/VT after 3 shocks - PEA without reversible cause identified - Persistent arrest > 5 min - Suspected tamponade or active bleeding 6. Internal cardiac massage during open exploration 7. Identify + treat cause: control bleeding, evacuate tamponade, repair injury, ECMO if cardiogenic shock **Drug differences**: - Avoid bolus epinephrine (severe HTN, intracardiac complications) - Use vasopressin or norepi infusion - Amiodarone for VF/VT - Calcium for hyperkalemia / Ca channel blocker toxicity **ECMO / ECLS**: bridge to recovery / transplant; rapid deployment improves survival in refractory. **Outcomes**: CALS protocol implementation improves survival from cardiac arrest after cardiac surgery to ~ 50%+ (vs 17% standard ACLS). **Training**: STS publishes CALS course + simulation curriculum; ICU + OR teams should be familiar + drilled.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'Basic science: cardiac arrest + cardiopulmonary resuscitation in surgical patient

คำถาม: post-cardiac surgery cardiac arrest — special protocol';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Avoid all communication"},{"label":"B","text":"Adverse event management + communication — open disclosure + patient safety"},{"label":"C","text":"Blame individual staff"},{"label":"D","text":"Hide information"},{"label":"E","text":"Refuse to discuss with patient"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Adverse event management + communication — open disclosure + patient safety**: (1) **Immediate response**: - Address ongoing medical care first (treat patient, stabilize, escalate) - Document accurately + factually; (2) **Open disclosure / ''Sorry Works''**: - Communicate transparently with patient + family - Express empathy + concern (apology for distress experienced, not necessarily admission of fault) - Explain what happened in understandable language - Discuss what investigation will be undertaken - Discuss plan for ongoing care + how to prevent recurrence - Avoid speculation + blame; - Evidence: open disclosure REDUCES litigation + improves trust (Michigan Open Disclosure, COPIC, Kaiser studies); (3) **Apology laws / ''I''m sorry'' laws** — many jurisdictions (~ 39 US states, multiple international) protect expressions of empathy from being used as admission of liability; check local; (4) **Root Cause Analysis (RCA)** — systematic event analysis: - Multidisciplinary team - Timeline reconstruction - Identify contributing factors (people, process, equipment, environment, communication) - ''Just culture'' — system vs individual - Develop action plan - Implement + monitor; (5) **M&M Conferences** — surgical tradition: - Case-based learning - Educational + safety improvement - Confidential (peer review protection) + non-punitive in best practice; (6) **Quality improvement processes**: - Failure Mode + Effects Analysis (FMEA) — proactive risk assessment - PDSA cycles (Plan-Do-Study-Act) - Lean / Six Sigma methodology; (7) **Documentation principles**: - Contemporaneous + factual - Avoid speculation, blame, emotion - Late entries marked + dated - Original records preserved; (8) **Legal considerations** when adverse event: - Notify risk management / hospital administration - Consult legal counsel - Maintain communication with patient (open disclosure within legal framework) - Quality of care matters AND communication matters — both reduce litigation - ''Disclose + offer'' programs (e.g., University of Michigan) — proactive disclosure + apology + compensation — reduces overall claims + costs; (9) **Patient safety culture**: - Just culture - Blameless reporting (incident reports, near-miss reporting) - Leadership commitment - Continuous learning; (10) **Personal impact**: - Second victim phenomenon — physician/team also affected by adverse outcome - Peer support, mental health support, debriefing - Burnout prevention

---

**Adverse event management + open disclosure** — central to modern patient safety + culture. **Open disclosure** (Australia, UK, US trends — Joint Commission, AHA, ACOG advocate): 1. **Acknowledge** the event happened 2. **Empathize** + offer sincere apology for impact 3. **Explain** in understandable terms what happened (factually, without speculation) 4. **Discuss** investigation + steps to prevent recurrence 5. **Continue** care + communication 6. **Compensation** if appropriate **Evidence**: open disclosure programs (Michigan, COPIC, Kaiser, VA): - Decreased litigation + costs - Improved patient satisfaction - Improved staff morale - Improved safety culture **Apology laws**: ~ 39 US states + many international jurisdictions protect expressions of empathy/sympathy from being used as admission of liability. Allows physicians to apologize without legal jeopardy. **Root Cause Analysis (RCA)** principles: - System focus, not individual blame - Identify contributing factors (5 Whys, Ishikawa fishbone) - Generate corrective actions - Implement + monitor - ''Just culture'' — distinguish system error vs individual reckless behavior vs honest mistake **''Just culture''** (Marx, Reason): - Three behaviors: human error (console), at-risk (coach), reckless (sanction) - Encourages reporting + learning - Removes fear of blame for honest mistake **Failure Mode + Effects Analysis (FMEA)** — proactive: anticipate failure modes before they occur; mitigate risk. **PDSA cycle** (Plan-Do-Study-Act) — quality improvement framework. **M&M Conference** — surgical learning tradition; case-based; peer review protection; educational not punitive in optimal practice. **Documentation** in adverse events: factual + contemporaneous + non-judgmental; avoid speculation, opinion, blame; legal protection by clear documentation. **Second victim phenomenon** — clinician/team distress after adverse event affecting patient: physical, psychological, professional impact; peer support, debriefing, mental health resources critical; programs like RISE (Resilience in Stressful Events) at Johns Hopkins. **Disclose + Offer Programs** (University of Michigan, others) — proactive disclosure of error + apology + compensation offer — reduces overall claims, costs, and patient harm.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'ระบบ EMS / quality / business of medicine: medical malpractice + surgical complications

คำถาม: how to handle adverse outcome + communication';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Verbal consent sufficient"},{"label":"B","text":"Informed consent — ethical + legal cornerstone"},{"label":"C","text":"Skip discussion of risks"},{"label":"D","text":"Coerce decisions"},{"label":"E","text":"No documentation needed"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Informed consent — ethical + legal cornerstone**: (1) **Elements of informed consent**: - **Disclosure**: nature of procedure, indication, risks (material risks), benefits, alternatives (including no treatment), prognosis - **Comprehension**: patient understands (assess with teach-back) - **Voluntariness**: not coerced - **Competence/Capacity**: decision-making capacity present - **Authorization**: explicit consent; (2) **Standards for disclosure** (vary by jurisdiction): - **Professional / reasonable physician**: what a reasonable physician would disclose (older standard) - **Reasonable patient (material risk)**: what a reasonable patient would want to know — modern preferred standard - **Subjective patient**: what this specific patient would want; (3) **Capacity assessment** — 4 components (MacArthur): - Understand information - Appreciate situation + consequences - Reason about options - Communicate choice; (4) **Capacity vs competence**: - Capacity is clinical judgment, decision-specific, fluctuates - Competence is legal determination - Both required for valid consent; (5) **Special situations**: - **Emergency**: implied consent for life-saving treatment when capacity absent + no surrogate available - **Surrogate decision-maker**: legal hierarchy (spouse, adult child, parent, sibling per state law); follow advance directive / patient''s prior expressed wishes (substituted judgment); best interests if no expressed wishes - **Pediatric**: parent / legal guardian; assent of child as developmentally appropriate; exceptions: emancipated minor, mature minor doctrine, specific medical issues (STI, contraception, mental health, substance use depending on jurisdiction) - **Pregnancy**: maternal autonomy paramount; competing fetal interests legally + ethically complex - **Cognitive impairment**: assess capacity decision-by-decision; involve family + surrogate; advance directives - **Jehovah''s Witness + blood refusal**: respect adult capacitated patient; pediatric — court intervention may be needed (best interest of child); document + plan accordingly; (6) **Documentation**: signed consent form + procedure note documenting discussion; teach-back; questions answered; (7) **Refusal of treatment**: equally valid right; document discussion + understanding; offer second opinion + reconsider; counsel of consequences without coercion; (8) **Withdrawal / withholding life-sustaining treatment**: same ethical principle as not initiating; supported by ethics committees, palliative care, legal frameworks; symptom management during withdrawal (opioid + benzodiazepine for dyspnea/anxiety); not euthanasia; (9) **Cultural + religious considerations**: explore + respect; interpreter services; family-centered decision-making in some cultures; (10) **Ethics consultation** for complex/disputed: hospital ethics committee resource; (11) **Conflicts of interest**: disclose; research consent additional layer; IRB oversight

---

**Informed Consent** — ethical + legal foundation of surgical practice. Required for all surgical procedures (with limited exceptions like emergent life-saving in unconscious patient). **Four elements**: 1. **Disclosure** — adequate information 2. **Comprehension** — patient understands 3. **Voluntariness** — free of coercion 4. **Authorization** — explicit consent **Disclosure standards** (jurisdiction-dependent): - **Professional / reasonable physician**: traditional — what reasonable physician would disclose - **Material risk / reasonable patient** (Canterbury v. Spence 1972, US): modern preferred — what reasonable patient would want to know; includes common risks + serious uncommon risks - **Subjective patient**: rare — what this particular patient would want **Capacity** — clinical determination, decision-specific, fluctuating: - Understand information - Appreciate situation + consequences - Reason about options - Communicate choice MacArthur Competence Assessment Tool — standardized. **Competence** — legal determination (court). **Special situations**: 1. **Emergency** — implied consent for life-saving in incapacitated patient without available surrogate; treatment to extent reasonable + necessary 2. **Surrogate decision-making** — hierarchy by state law: typically spouse, adult child, parent, sibling, other relative, close friend; follow advance directive if exists; use substituted judgment (what patient would want); best interests if no expressed wishes 3. **Pediatric** — parental consent + age-appropriate assent; emancipated minor, mature minor doctrine, specific conditions (reproductive, mental health, substance use) — varies by state 4. **Cognitive impairment / dementia** — capacity decision-by-decision; advance directives; surrogate 5. **Blood refusal (Jehovah''s Witness)** — adult capacitated patient''s right; pediatric — best interest of child may override (court intervention if needed) 6. **Pregnancy** — maternal autonomy paramount; some legal cases test 7. **Substance use, intoxication** — capacity assessment carefully 8. **Mental illness** — does not equate to incapacity; assess specifically **Refusal of treatment** — same right as consent; document + counsel; not coercion. **Withdrawing / withholding life-sustaining treatment** — ethically same as not initiating; well-established legal + ethical framework; symptom management. **Cultural + religious sensitivity** — interpreter, family involvement, cultural humility. **Ethics consultation** — for complex / disputed cases. **Conflicts of interest** disclosure — relevant to consent (research, financial relationships). **Research consent** — IRB + additional protections (HIPAA, informed consent specific to research).'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'ระบบ EMS / professionalism: ethics + informed consent

คำถาม: surgical informed consent + complex situations';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Single organ transplant only"},{"label":"B","text":"Simultaneous Pancreas-Kidney (SPK) transplant evaluation — integrative approach"},{"label":"C","text":"No transplant consideration"},{"label":"D","text":"Dialysis lifelong only"},{"label":"E","text":"Discharge home with hospice referral"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Simultaneous Pancreas-Kidney (SPK) transplant evaluation — integrative approach**: (1) **Candidacy assessment for SPK**: - Type 1 DM with ESRD - Brittle DM with poor quality of life (hypoglycemia unawareness, severe complications) - No major medical/surgical contraindications - Adequate functional status to undergo surgery + immunosuppression - Psychological + social support; (2) **Pre-transplant evaluation comprehensive**: - **Cardiac**: stress test (often pharmacologic — adenosine, dobutamine); coronary angiogram given prior MI (recurrent ischemia risk); echo (LV function, valves); 24h Holter if arrhythmia history - **Pulmonary**: PFT; CXR - **Infectious**: HIV, HBV, HCV, CMV, EBV, VZV, TB (IGRA/skin test), syphilis, strongyloides (depending on region); vaccination updates - **Cancer screening**: age-appropriate (colonoscopy, mammogram, Pap, PSA), thorough skin exam - **Endocrine**: thyroid, parathyroid (HPT common in ESRD) - **GI**: hepatitis serology + LFT; H. pylori; - **Vascular**: peripheral arterial — both for transplant access + future considerations - **Dental**: clearance, source control - **Psychiatric / psychosocial**: depression, anxiety, substance use, adherence assessment, support system - **Nutrition**: optimize - **Smoking cessation absolute**; (3) **Listing for transplant** — UNOS / OPTN matching system; - HLA typing, panel reactive antibodies (PRA), crossmatch - Allocation algorithm by region; - Wait list management; (4) **Surgical considerations**: - Pancreas transplant + kidney transplant — combined operation - Pancreas: portal vs systemic venous drainage; bladder vs enteric exocrine drainage - Kidney: heterotopic in iliac fossa - Iliac vessel access + arterial reconstruction; (5) **Immunosuppression** post-transplant: - Induction: anti-thymocyte globulin (ATG) or basiliximab - Maintenance: tacrolimus + mycophenolate + steroid (taper) - Adjustments per complications - Lifelong; (6) **Outcomes**: - SPK > Pancreas alone in long-term graft survival - 5-year patient survival 90%+, pancreas graft 70-80%, kidney 80-85% - Quality of life: insulin-free, improved DM complications progression - Hypoglycemia unawareness resolved typically; (7) **Post-transplant management**: - Immunosuppression monitoring (drug levels) - Rejection surveillance (creatinine, amylase, glucose) - Infection prophylaxis (PJP — TMP-SMX; CMV — valganciclovir; fungal — fluconazole) - Cancer surveillance (increased risk) - Cardiovascular risk management - Lifestyle - Adherence support; (8) **Family + support involvement** essential; (9) **Long-term complications**: chronic rejection, infections, malignancy (especially skin, PTLD), recurrence of underlying disease (rare in T1DM)

---

**Simultaneous Pancreas-Kidney (SPK) Transplantation** — option for selected T1DM with ESRD: free from dialysis + insulin; improved QOL + survival vs dialysis alone or kidney alone for many. **Indications**: 1. T1DM with ESRD (creatinine clearance < 20-30, on dialysis or pre-emptive) 2. Brittle T1DM with hypoglycemia unawareness or severe complications without ESRD (pancreas alone — PA — option, but lower graft survival) **Patient selection considerations**: - Cardiac risk significant in DM patients — comprehensive evaluation - Vascular disease assessment - Psychosocial readiness + adherence - Avoid in active malignancy, active infection, severe non-correctable comorbidity, substance use **Three main pancreas transplant types**: 1. **SPK** (Simultaneous Pancreas-Kidney) — best graft survival of pancreas options 2. **PAK** (Pancreas After Kidney) — if pancreas needs after prior kidney transplant 3. **PA / PTA** (Pancreas Transplant Alone) — for hypoglycemia unawareness without ESRD; lower graft survival **Surgical technique variations**: - **Exocrine drainage**: enteric (most common modern — to Roux limb of jejunum) vs bladder (older — easier monitoring of urinary amylase but UTI + dehydration + acidosis problems) - **Endocrine drainage**: portal (more physiologic) vs systemic (iliac vein — more common) - Concurrent kidney transplant to ipsilateral or contralateral iliac fossa **Immunosuppression** typical: - Induction: ATG (anti-thymocyte globulin) or basiliximab (anti-IL-2R) - Maintenance: tacrolimus + mycophenolate + steroid (often tapered to low-dose or stopped) **Outcomes (USA, UNOS data)**: - 5-yr patient survival ~ 90%+ - 5-yr pancreas graft survival ~ 70-80% - 5-yr kidney graft survival ~ 80-85% - Insulin-free for vast majority while graft functions - Improved diabetic complication progression (nephropathy, retinopathy, neuropathy) - Resolved hypoglycemia unawareness **Post-transplant management**: - Immunosuppression monitoring + adjustment - Rejection surveillance: creatinine, glucose, amylase (pancreas) - Infection prophylaxis: PJP, CMV, fungal - Vaccine schedule update - Cancer surveillance (skin especially, PTLD) - Cardiovascular risk - Adherence support **Islet cell transplantation** — alternative to whole-organ pancreas; minimally invasive (percutaneous portal vein infusion); good for selected (hypoglycemia unawareness without ESRD); insulin independence rates improving but lower than whole-organ; multiple donors usually needed (CIT protocol). **Newer**: islet auto-transplantation post-pancreatectomy (chronic pancreatitis); stem cell-derived islet therapy (Vertex VX-880 + others in trial).'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 25 ปี Type 1 DM uncontrolled HbA1c 11.4 + multiple admit DKA + history of acute MI 1 year ago + ESRD on dialysis 2 years

Referral for kidney + pancreas transplant evaluation

คำถาม: pre-transplant workup + integrative considerations';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No special considerations"},{"label":"B","text":"Post-liver transplant survivorship + planning pregnancy — integrative care"},{"label":"C","text":"Stop all medications during pregnancy"},{"label":"D","text":"Refuse to allow pregnancy"},{"label":"E","text":"Discontinue HBV antiviral"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Post-liver transplant survivorship + planning pregnancy — integrative care**: (1) **Multidisciplinary clinic**: transplant hepatology, transplant surgery, MFM (maternal-fetal medicine), obstetrics, pharmacy, social work, mental health; (2) **Pre-conception counseling**: - Timing: ≥ 1-2 years post-transplant with stable graft function + immunosuppression - Stable lab parameters: normal LFT, stable creatinine, no rejection in 6-12 months - Medication review + adjustment (see below) - Disease control (HBV undetectable, HCC surveillance) - Maternal health optimization (BMI, BP, glycemic, vaccines) - Genetic counseling if disease has heritable component; (3) **Immunosuppression in pregnancy**: - **Tacrolimus** — safe in pregnancy; clearance increases — may need dose increase (monitor levels) - **Cyclosporine** — safe alternative; similar - **Azathioprine** — safe in pregnancy + breastfeeding (despite black box warning, evidence supports safety for fetus) - **Mycophenolate (MMF, MPA)** — TERATOGENIC — fetal loss + congenital anomalies (cleft, ear, cardiac) — STOP 6 weeks before conception + use alternative (azathioprine) - **mTOR inhibitors (sirolimus, everolimus)** — limited data; preferable to avoid; switch if possible - **Steroids** — low-dose acceptable - **Belatacept** — limited data - **Antivirals (entecavir, tenofovir for HBV)** — tenofovir preferred in pregnancy (better safety data); continue; (4) **HBV-specific considerations**: - Continue antiviral suppression - Tenofovir preferred (TDF or TAF) over entecavir in pregnancy - HBV transmission to neonate: HBIG + HBV vaccine at birth + appropriate maternal viral suppression - Monitor maternal viral load + LFT - HCC surveillance continues; (5) **HCC surveillance**: - 5-yr post-transplant: AFP + imaging (US/CT/MRI) q6-12 mo standard for transplanted HCC - Lifelong surveillance; (6) **Pregnancy management** (high-risk): - Increased risks: HT, GDM, preeclampsia, preterm birth, SGA, miscarriage, abruption, infection - Multidisciplinary high-risk OB - Increased fetal surveillance + maternal monitoring - Vaccinations updated (acellular pertussis Tdap, influenza inactivated) - Avoid live vaccines (yellow fever, MMR, varicella); (7) **Delivery planning**: - Vaginal delivery preferred when feasible - Cesarean for obstetric indications - Anti-rejection medication continued throughout - Stress-dose steroids may be needed - Antibiotic prophylaxis if cesarean (standard); (8) **Postpartum**: - Continue immunosuppression - Lactation: most immunosuppressants compatible (tacrolimus, cyclosporine, azathioprine, prednisone); mycophenolate AVOID - Postpartum surveillance for rejection (immune changes post-delivery) - HCC surveillance resumes per schedule; (9) **Family planning + contraception**: - During fertile years + spacing pregnancies - Reliable methods; IUD (copper preferred over hormonal — controversial efficacy in immunosuppressed; reasonable); barrier; permanent if family complete; (10) **Long-term**: continue lifelong post-transplant care; family + caregiver support; psychological wellbeing

---

**Pregnancy after liver transplant** — increasingly common as transplant outcomes improve. **Pre-conception planning**: - ≥ 1-2 years post-transplant - Stable graft function (LFT, Cr, immunosuppression levels) - No rejection within 6-12 months - Disease-specific control (HBV, HCV, autoimmune all in remission) - HCC: appropriate surveillance + acceptable disease-free interval (lifelong surveillance) **Immunosuppression in pregnancy** — major modifications: 1. **Tacrolimus**: CONTINUE; pregnancy-safe; clearance ↑ → may need dose increase (level monitoring) 2. **Cyclosporine**: CONTINUE; alternative to tacrolimus; safe 3. **Azathioprine**: CONTINUE — despite black box warning, evidence supports fetal safety 4. **Prednisone / methylprednisolone**: low-dose CONTINUE; safe 5. **Mycophenolate (MMF, MPA)**: STOP — TERATOGENIC (cleft palate, microtia, congenital heart, fetal loss); switch to azathioprine ≥ 6 weeks pre-conception 6. **mTOR inhibitors (sirolimus, everolimus)**: limited data; switch off if possible 7. **Belatacept**: limited data **Specific disease considerations**: - **HBV**: continue antiviral suppression; **tenofovir TDF/TAF preferred** in pregnancy (entecavir limited data); newborn HBIG + HBV vaccine; maternal viral load monitoring - **HCV**: cured most patients with DAAs; if active — defer pregnancy until treated - **Autoimmune (PBC, PSC, AIH)**: continue azathioprine; monitor flares - **NASH/MASH**: weight management - **HCC**: continued surveillance regardless of pregnancy **Maternal complications increased**: HT, preeclampsia, GDM, infection, anemia, preterm birth, bleeding (cesarean), graft dysfunction risk. **Fetal complications increased**: prematurity, IUGR/SGA, lower birth weight, miscarriage (some studies); congenital anomalies usually not increased (with appropriate medication management). **Surveillance during pregnancy**: more frequent OB visits, fetal monitoring (growth, biophysical), maternal labs (LFT, Cr, drug levels, glucose, viral load). **Delivery**: vaginal preferred when feasible; cesarean for obstetric indications; routine perioperative antibiotic; anesthesia consult. **Lactation compatibility**: tacrolimus, cyclosporine, azathioprine, prednisone, hydroxychloroquine all generally compatible (modify per Lactmed); mycophenolate AVOID. **Contraception** during transplant + between pregnancies: reliable + safe — IUD (copper or hormonal), barrier, hormonal (caution with drug interactions), permanent if family complete.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 40 ปี post-living-donor liver transplant 5 ปี for HCC + HBV cirrhosis — มา outpatient clinic for routine surveillance + planning for second pregnancy

Lab: stable graft function, HBV DNA undetectable on antiviral, immunosuppression on low-dose tacrolimus monotherapy

คำถาม: integrative survivorship + reproductive planning';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Continue PPI alone forever"},{"label":"B","text":"Post-sleeve gastrectomy GERD complications + weight regain — multidisciplinary"},{"label":"C","text":"Stop all medications"},{"label":"D","text":"Refuse all interventions"},{"label":"E","text":"Discharge home"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Post-sleeve gastrectomy GERD complications + weight regain — multidisciplinary**: (1) **Workup**: - EGD (already done) — confirm Barrett''s, biopsy, exclude dysplasia, anatomic assessment (hiatal hernia, sleeve anatomy) - High-resolution manometry — esophageal motility - 24h pH study off PPI — quantify reflux burden - Barium swallow — anatomy of sleeve + reflux dynamics - Possible gastric emptying study; (2) **GERD post-sleeve mechanism**: - Removal of fundus + LES support + His angle disruption - High intragastric pressure (narrow tube) - Hiatal hernia (often pre-existing) - Stenosis at incisura, twisting of sleeve - Decreased gastric compliance; (3) **Medical optimization**: - High-dose PPI (consider esomeprazole 40 mg BID) - H2 blocker bedtime adjunct - Alginate (Gaviscon Advance) post-meal + bedtime - Lifestyle: weight loss if indicated, head of bed elevation, no late meals, avoid trigger foods - Sucralfate for esophagitis; (4) **Barrett''s surveillance + management**: - EGD with biopsies (Seattle protocol) q3-5 yr no dysplasia, more frequent if dysplasia - Endoscopic ablation (RFA) for dysplasia/intramucosal carcinoma - PPI lifelong; (5) **Revision bariatric surgery options for severe GERD**: - **Conversion to Roux-en-Y gastric bypass (RYGB)** — gold standard for sleeve failure + GERD: eliminates reflux + addresses weight regain + better metabolic outcomes; technically challenging revision - **Magnetic sphincter augmentation (LINX device)** — for selected without hiatal hernia or severe esophagitis; can be done post-sleeve - **Hiatal hernia repair + sleeve adjustment** — if HH primary issue - **Fundoplication impossible** post-sleeve (no fundus); (6) **Weight regain workup** — common after bariatric: - Behavioral (eating habits, portion, snacking, beverages) - Hormonal adaptation (ghrelin recovers, GLP-1 may decrease) - Anatomic (sleeve dilation, gastrogastric fistula) - Psychological (food addiction, binge eating, depression) - Medical (medication weight gain — antidepressants, antipsychotics); (7) **Weight regain management**: - Nutrition + behavioral counseling - Pharmacotherapy: GLP-1 agonists (semaglutide, tirzepatide) — increasingly used post-bariatric; counsel on possible reduced response - Revision surgery if anatomic issue + severe regain - Endoscopic options (re-sleeve, plication) — selected; (8) **Multidisciplinary**: bariatric surgery, GI, nutrition, psychology, primary care; long-term integrated follow-up; (9) **Patient counseling**: realistic expectations, lifelong management

---

**Sleeve gastrectomy + GERD** — major issue. Sleeve gastrectomy has GERD as major long-term complication (10-30% develop new or worsened GERD; even higher with longer follow-up). Some develop Barrett''s esophagus (~ 3-15% at 5+ years per cohorts), potentially with dysplasia / adenocarcinoma. **Pre-op evaluation should screen for GERD severity** — patients with severe pre-op GERD may not be ideal sleeve candidates; some advocate RYGB primary for these patients. **Mechanisms of post-sleeve GERD**: 1. Anatomic — disruption of His angle, removal of fundus, reduced LES support 2. Physiologic — high intragastric pressure (narrow tube), reduced compliance 3. Hiatal hernia (pre-existing or new) 4. Sleeve anatomy issues — stenosis at incisura, twist, dilated proximal pouch 5. Delayed gastric emptying **Management ladder**: 1. **Medical optimization**: high-dose PPI (potentially BID), H2 blocker adjunct, alginate, lifestyle, weight management 2. **EGD with Barrett''s surveillance**: Seattle protocol biopsies; treat dysplasia (RFA/EMR) 3. **Workup**: manometry, pH study, barium swallow, gastric emptying 4. **Surgical revision** for refractory: - **Conversion to RYGB** — most effective for GERD + addresses weight regain; complex revision but acceptable outcomes - **LINX (magnetic sphincter augmentation)** — selected without severe esophagitis or large hiatal hernia; preserves anatomy - **Hiatal hernia repair** if primary anatomic issue 5. **Fundoplication NOT possible** post-sleeve (no fundus available) **Weight regain post-bariatric** — common (20-40% at 10 yr): - Behavioral + dietary - Hormonal adaptation - Anatomic (sleeve dilation, gastrogastric fistula in RYGB) - Psychological - Medication weight gain Management: behavioral counseling, nutrition support, GLP-1 + dual agonists (semaglutide 2.4 mg, tirzepatide 15 mg increasingly used post-bariatric with good response in many), revision surgery for anatomic issue + severe regain, endoscopic options (re-sleeve, plication). **GLP-1 + GIP/GLP-1 dual agonists post-bariatric**: increasingly utilized for weight regain or insufficient initial response; semaglutide (Wegovy, Ozempic), tirzepatide (Mounjaro/Zepbound); response variable but many achieve meaningful additional weight loss; long-term data accumulating. **Multidisciplinary lifelong care** — essential for bariatric patient; integrate medical, surgical, nutritional, psychological, behavioral approaches.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 50 ปี post-bariatric sleeve gastrectomy 5 ปีก่อน — มาด้วยอาการ chronic GERD severe + Barrett''s segment 2 cm + esophagitis grade C; PPI optimal failed; weight regain 15 kg from nadir

คำถาม: complex management';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Continue all aggressive treatment"},{"label":"B","text":"Advanced HCC progression with limited treatment options — integrative palliative + serious illness conversations"},{"label":"C","text":"Stop all medications immediately + send home"},{"label":"D","text":"Refuse to discuss prognosis"},{"label":"E","text":"Continue all curative treatments aggressively"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Advanced HCC progression with limited treatment options — integrative palliative + serious illness conversations**: (1) **Multidisciplinary team meeting**: medical oncology, hepatology, palliative care, social work, chaplain, family medicine; (2) **Goals of care discussion** with patient + family — serious illness conversation framework (Ariadne Labs / Atul Gawande): - Understanding of illness + prognosis - What''s important to patient (values, fears, hopes) - What outcomes they want to avoid - What functional trade-offs acceptable - Family wishes + dynamics - Cultural + spiritual considerations; (3) **Prognostic estimation**: - Advanced HCC + Child B + progression on first-line + ECOG 2 → median survival 3-6 months - Be honest but compassionate — ''hope for the best, prepare for the worst'' - Surprise question: ''would I be surprised if patient died in 12 months?'' — useful prognostic question; (4) **Treatment options to consider** (decreasing intensity): - Second-line systemic therapy (lenvatinib, sorafenib, regorafenib, cabozantinib, ramucirumab if AFP > 400) — limited efficacy; weigh toxicity vs benefit; ECOG 2 borderline candidacy - Locoregional therapy (TACE, Y90, SBRT) — for liver-predominant; limited utility in advanced - **Best supportive care + palliative care** — focus on QOL + symptom management; (5) **Concurrent palliative care from diagnosis of advanced disease** (per Temel JCO 2010 NEJM 2010 — improves QOL + may extend survival); not ''palliative or curative'' — both can coexist; (6) **Symptom management**: - **Pain**: WHO ladder; opioids — careful dose-adjust in hepatic impairment (avoid morphine accumulation in renal/hepatic, use hydromorphone or fentanyl; morphine OK at adjusted dose with monitoring); coadjuvants for neuropathic - **Ascites**: large-volume paracentesis as needed; sodium restriction + diuretic adjusted for hepatic dysfunction; PleurX catheter consideration for recurrent symptomatic - **Hepatic encephalopathy**: lactulose, rifaximin; treat precipitants - **Pruritus**: anti-histamine, cholestyramine, sertraline, naltrexone (caution) - **Nausea**: ondansetron, haloperidol, metoclopramide - **Fatigue**: address reversible (anemia, depression); pacing - **Anorexia / cachexia**: nutritional counseling; appetite stimulants limited efficacy (megestrol, mirtazapine, low-dose steroid); enteral if quality of life maintained - **Anxiety + depression**: SSRIs (sertraline, escitalopram), counseling - **Dyspnea**: oxygen, opioid (low-dose); (7) **Advance care planning + advance directive**: - Healthcare proxy designation - Living will - DNR / POLST discussion - Specific care preferences (intubation, dialysis, artificial nutrition); (8) **Hospice eligibility + referral**: - Medicare benefit if life expectancy ≤ 6 months + focus on comfort - Hospice services: comprehensive symptom management, nursing, social work, chaplain, volunteer, bereavement support, equipment, medications - Settings: home with hospice (preferred when feasible), inpatient hospice unit, residential, hospital; (9) **Family support**: - Anticipatory grief + counseling - Caregiver burden + respite - Family meeting facilitator (palliative care, social work) - Children''s understanding (age-appropriate communication; child life specialists if hospital-based) - Cultural + spiritual rituals respected - Practical support (legal, financial, social services); (10) **Spiritual care**: chaplain consultation; cultural + religious practices integrated; (11) **Bereavement**: continue support for family for 12+ months after death; identify complicated grief; (12) **Care team self-care**: addressing ''second patient'' issues — clinician grief, burnout prevention

---

**Advanced cancer integrative palliative care** — concurrent palliative care from diagnosis of advanced disease improves outcomes (Temel NEJM 2010 — early integrated palliative care in NSCLC improved QOL + mood + survival). **Serious illness conversation framework** (Ariadne Labs, Gawande): 1. Set up the conversation (permission, dedicated time) 2. Assess understanding + information preferences 3. Share prognosis (sensitive but honest) 4. Explore key topics: - What''s important to you? - What are your fears + worries? - What goals do you have? - What outcomes are unacceptable? - How much are you willing to go through for the chance of more time? 5. Close the conversation (recommendation, plan) **Prognostication tools**: - Surprise question: ''would I be surprised if this patient died in 12 months?'' - Performance status (ECOG, Karnofsky) - Disease-specific prognostic models - Palliative Performance Scale (PPS) - PaP (Palliative Prognostic) Score **Symptom management in end-stage liver disease + cancer**: - Pain (opioid dose adjustment): avoid morphine accumulation in renal/hepatic dysfunction; hydromorphone (renal/hepatic safer), fentanyl (hepatic OK, transdermal stable in cachectic), methadone (caution, prolonged QT, complex pharmacology) - Ascites: paracentesis, diuretic (judicious), albumin replacement, PleurX catheter for recurrent - Hepatic encephalopathy: lactulose, rifaximin; treat precipitants (infection, GI bleed, dehydration, medications, constipation) - Pruritus: cholestyramine, sertraline, naltrexone, antihistamine - Anorexia / cachexia: nutritional support if QOL maintained; megestrol, mirtazapine, low-dose steroid (limited benefit); cannabinoids variable - Fatigue: address reversible (anemia, depression, hypothyroid, hypogonadism); methylphenidate selective benefit - Dyspnea: opioid (low-dose morphine 2.5 mg PO q4h or equivalent — central effect on dyspnea perception), oxygen, fan, positioning, anxiolytic **Advance care planning**: - Healthcare proxy designation - Living will - POLST / MOLST (Physician Orders for Life-Sustaining Treatment) — actionable medical orders portable across settings - Code status discussion **Hospice eligibility (Medicare US)**: life expectancy ≤ 6 months + comfort-focused care + foregoing curative intent — hospice provides comprehensive interdisciplinary services (nursing, social work, chaplain, home health aide, bereavement, equipment, medications). **Family / caregiver support**: anticipatory grief, complicated grief screening, caregiver burden assessment, respite, social work, financial counseling, children''s services (Child Life), bereavement support 12+ months. **Cultural + spiritual sensitivity**: language, religious practices, family hierarchy, decision-making customs, end-of-life rituals — integrate into care plan. **Clinician wellbeing**: burnout prevention, debriefing, peer support, mental health resources — recognized critical for sustainable palliative + serious illness care delivery.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 60 ปี diagnosed with HCC 6 months ago — Child-Pugh B + advanced HCC + portal vein invasion + ascites + recently completed atezolizumab/bevacizumab but progression + ECOG 2 + พ่อแม่และบุตรหลายคน + ครอบครัวยอมรับยาก

คำถาม: integrative palliative + end-of-life care';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Antibiotic alone outpatient"},{"label":"B","text":"Post-lung transplant respiratory deterioration — broad differential, expedited workup"},{"label":"C","text":"Increase immunosuppression empirically"},{"label":"D","text":"Outpatient observation"},{"label":"E","text":"Stop all medications"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Post-lung transplant respiratory deterioration — broad differential, expedited workup**: (1) **Differential**: - **Acute rejection** (most common cause of decline first 6 mo) - cellular (T-cell mediated) more common than antibody-mediated - Diagnosis: bronchoscopy + transbronchial biopsy (gold standard) - Treatment: pulse steroid (methylprednisolone 1 g × 3 days), augment immunosuppression; ATG/rituximab for severe/AMR - **Infection** (also common): - CMV (q month surveillance for first 6-12 mo); treat valganciclovir/ganciclovir - PJP (Pneumocystis jirovecii — prophylaxis TMP-SMX, dapsone if intolerant); treat high-dose TMP-SMX + steroid - Fungal (Aspergillus most concerning in lung transplant) — voriconazole, posaconazole - Bacterial pneumonia (community + nosocomial) — culture-directed antibiotic - Atypical (Mycoplasma, Legionella, Chlamydia) - **Reperfusion injury / primary graft dysfunction** — usually earlier (< 72h post-transplant) - **Airway complications**: anastomotic dehiscence, stenosis, malacia — bronchoscopy + intervention - **Pulmonary embolism** — high risk post-major surgery + hypercoagulable - **Cardiac**: rejection if heart transplant component, fluid overload - **Drug toxicity**: tacrolimus, mycophenolate, sirolimus pulmonary toxicity; (2) **Workup**: - CBC + diff, BMP, LFT, lactate, troponin, BNP - Respiratory cultures (sputum, bronchoscopy with BAL — culture for bacteria, virus, fungus, AFB) - CMV PCR (blood), galactomannan (Aspergillus), β-D-glucan - Tacrolimus + other drug levels (already checked — therapeutic) - ABG - CXR + CT chest with contrast (if Cr permits) - ECG, echo if cardiac concern - Bronchoscopy + transbronchial biopsy — for rejection vs infection; (3) **Empiric treatment** while workup in progress: - Broad-spectrum antibiotic (cefepime + vancomycin) - Antifungal if high risk (voriconazole) - CMV antiviral if suspected - Consider pulse steroid if rejection strongly suspected after infection ruled out; (4) **Multidisciplinary**: transplant pulmonology, ID, surgery, ICU; (5) **Long-term**: rejection prophylaxis (immunosuppression adherence, drug levels), infection prophylaxis (PJP, CMV, fungal), surveillance bronchoscopies, pulmonary rehab, vaccinations (inactivated), lifestyle

---

**Post-lung transplant respiratory deterioration** — broad differential; rejection + infection top considerations; both can overlap; biopsy often needed to distinguish. **Common causes by time after transplant**: - **< 30 days**: primary graft dysfunction, bacterial pneumonia, anastomotic issues, hyperacute rejection (rare with cross-match) - **30 days - 6 months**: acute cellular rejection peak, CMV, PJP (if not on prophylaxis), bacterial, Aspergillus, herpes - **6 months - 1 year**: late acute rejection, chronic rejection emerging (BOS — bronchiolitis obliterans syndrome / CLAD — chronic lung allograft dysfunction), community-acquired infections, CMV later if no prophylaxis - **> 1 year**: chronic rejection (CLAD/BOS) main long-term threat, infections, malignancy (PTLD, skin) **Acute rejection**: - **Cellular** (T-cell mediated) — more common; bronchoscopy + transbronchial biopsy (grading A0-A4 per ISHLT) - **Antibody-mediated (AMR)** — emerging recognition; DSA + biopsy with C4d staining; harder to diagnose **Bronchoscopy with BAL + transbronchial biopsy** — gold standard for: - Distinguishing rejection from infection - Identifying specific pathogen - Quantifying inflammation - Surveillance bronchoscopies routine first year **Common infections post-lung transplant**: 1. **CMV** — common; PCR surveillance; valganciclovir/ganciclovir prophylaxis + treatment 2. **PJP (P. jirovecii)** — TMP-SMX prophylaxis lifelong; high-dose TMP-SMX + steroid for treatment 3. **Aspergillus** — voriconazole prophylaxis often in early post-transplant; treatment voriconazole / isavuconazole / amphotericin 4. **Bacterial** — culture-directed; nosocomial vs community 5. **HSV / VZV / EBV (PTLD)** — antiviral prophylaxis (acyclovir/valacyclovir) **Chronic Lung Allograft Dysfunction (CLAD)** — main barrier to long-term survival post-lung transplant: - Bronchiolitis Obliterans Syndrome (BOS) — obstructive - Restrictive Allograft Syndrome (RAS) - 50% by 5 yr; limits long-term survival - Treatment options limited; some response to azithromycin (motility, anti-inflammatory), extracorporeal photopheresis, montelukast; re-transplantation in selected **Empiric treatment** while workup pending: balance treating likely conditions while waiting for tissue diagnosis; multidisciplinary team essential. **Drug interactions** — extensive: azoles (fluconazole, voriconazole, posaconazole) interact with calcineurin inhibitors (tacrolimus, cyclosporine) — increase levels; dose-adjust + monitor closely.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'ชายไทยอายุ 55 ปี smoker, COPD GOLD C, ผ่า lung transplant 6 weeks ago — มา ED ด้วยอาการ shortness of breath progressive 3 days + fever 38.4°C + cough + decreased exercise tolerance

VS: BP 124/78, HR 102, RR 24, SpO2 88% room air
CXR: bilateral infiltrates new vs prior baseline
Lab: WBC 14,400 (was 8,000), Cr 1.4 (baseline 1.0), tacrolimus level 12 ng/mL (target 10-15)

คำถาม: differential + workup';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Same as omphalocele"},{"label":"B","text":"Gastroschisis vs Omphalocele — distinct entities"},{"label":"C","text":"Observation only"},{"label":"D","text":"Discharge home"},{"label":"E","text":"Total bowel resection"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Gastroschisis vs Omphalocele — distinct entities**: **Gastroschisis**: defect right of umbilicus (paraumbilical), NO covering membrane, bowel exposed (often inflamed/thickened from amniotic fluid exposure), umbilical cord normal position, LOW association with other anomalies (5-10%) but high bowel atresia; **Omphalocele**: midline defect at umbilical cord, COVERED by amnion + peritoneum membrane (may rupture), liver + bowel inside sac, HIGH association with chromosomal (trisomy 13, 18, 21) + cardiac anomalies (30-50%), Beckwith-Wiedemann, pentalogy of Cantrell; **Management of gastroschisis**: (1) Immediate: cover exposed bowel with sterile saline-soaked gauze + cling wrap or bowel bag; NPO, NG decompression, IV fluid (large losses), IV antibiotic, thermoregulation (high losses → hypothermia); (2) Operative — primary closure if abdominal cavity can accommodate (no compartment syndrome); OR staged with **silo** (preformed silastic silo or surgical silo) → daily reduction over 5-10 days → delayed closure; (3) Post-op: TPN until bowel function returns (often weeks), gradual enteral feeds; (4) Complications: short gut syndrome, motility disorders, atresia (concurrent), feeding intolerance; (5) Omphalocele management: similar staged approach but slower (large defects); ''paint + wait'' (silver sulfadiazine, escharification) for giant defects; sac itself protects; associated anomaly workup essential (echo, karyotype, etc.); (6) Long-term: most do well; nutritional + developmental follow-up

---

**Abdominal wall defects** — two main: **Gastroschisis** vs **Omphalocele**. Differentiation critical for management + prognosis. Gastroschisis: right paraumbilical, no sac, inflamed bowel, fewer associations, primary or staged silo closure. Omphalocele: midline, intact sac, liver + bowel, MANY associated anomalies (cardiac 30-50%, chromosomal — trisomies, Beckwith-Wiedemann, Cantrell pentalogy), echo + karyotype workup essential. Both need NG decompression, IV fluid, thermoregulation, antibiotic, and surgical management (primary or staged silo). Outcomes generally good with modern care; long-term issues: feeding, growth, motility, short gut if extensive bowel resection.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'ทารกแรกเกิดอายุ 1 วัน born term, มาด้วย abdominal wall defect — bowel + liver exposed ที่ midline ไม่มี covering membrane

คำถาม: distinguish + management';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Force surgery"},{"label":"B","text":"Equivocal abdominal pain — observation + serial reassessment + targeted workup"},{"label":"C","text":"Discharge without follow-up"},{"label":"D","text":"Long-term opioid prescription"},{"label":"E","text":"Surgery indicated regardless"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Equivocal abdominal pain — observation + serial reassessment + targeted workup**: (1) **Serial abdominal exam** by same examiner — most valuable diagnostic tool; (2) **Active observation** in ED / observation unit 4-12h — many self-resolve OR develop clear features; (3) **Repeat labs** at 6-12h if not improving — WBC trend, CRP; (4) **Imaging** as guided: - US first (radiation-free, pelvic + abdominal) - CT if clinical worsening or persistent unclear - MRI if pregnant; (5) **Other differentials to consider** in young woman with RLQ pain: - GI: appendicitis (early or atypical), Meckel''s, mesenteric adenitis, Crohn''s terminal ileitis, infectious enteritis - GYN: ovarian cyst (rupture, torsion — surgical emergency), ectopic pregnancy (check β-hCG always), PID, endometriosis, mittelschmerz - GU: UTI, ureteral colic - Musculoskeletal: psoas, hip - Other: functional, anxiety-related; (6) **β-hCG mandatory** in reproductive-age female with abdominal pain; (7) **Discharge criteria**: - Clinical improvement - Pain controlled - Tolerating PO - Reliable patient + access to follow-up - Clear return precautions (worsening pain, fever, vomiting, inability to eat, peritonitis signs); (8) **Education** + follow-up clinic 24-48h; (9) **Document carefully** — return reasons, time of resolution, expected course

---

**Equivocal acute abdomen** — common scenario; balance between unnecessary surgery (negative laparotomy/laparoscopy ~ 10-15%) and missed serious diagnosis. **Diagnostic approach**: 1. Serial exam by same provider — most valuable 2. Active observation (4-12 hr) 3. Repeat labs (WBC trend) 4. Imaging escalation (US → CT) 5. β-hCG always in reproductive-age female 6. Consider gynecologic differentials in females Use ''safety netting'' — clear return precautions, follow-up. Use ''shared decision-making'' regarding observation vs intervention. Documentation important. **Pain management during observation**: appropriate analgesia does not mask diagnosis (clinical exam preserved with opioid administration per modern evidence — old dogma debunked). Multimodal analgesia preferred.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'หญิงไทยอายุ 25 ปี severe anxiety + abdominal pain RLQ + nausea but normal vitals + normal labs; previously suspected appendicitis but US negative + clinical improved overnight; planning discharge

คำถาม: management of equivocal abdominal pain';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No surveillance needed"},{"label":"B","text":"Cirrhosis comprehensive management + HCC surveillance"},{"label":"C","text":"Refer to hospice"},{"label":"D","text":"Stop all medications"},{"label":"E","text":"Annual labs only"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Cirrhosis comprehensive management + HCC surveillance**: (1) **HCC surveillance** in cirrhosis: - US ± AFP q6 months for at-risk (cirrhosis any etiology, chronic HBV without cirrhosis if Asian male > 40 / Asian female > 50 / Africans > 20 / family history HCC) - Multi-phase contrast CT or MRI if US suboptimal (obesity, fatty liver) or lesion detected - LI-RADS classification for indeterminate lesions; (2) **Variceal surveillance**: - EGD at diagnosis of cirrhosis - Repeat per Baveno criteria: small varices, no red signs → 2 yr; large or red signs → primary prophylaxis (NSBB or band) - On secondary prophylaxis (post-bleed, this patient) → continue NSBB + serial banding until eradication; (3) **Treat underlying liver disease**: - HBV: antiviral lifelong - HCV: DAA eradication (cure > 95%) - Alcohol: cessation absolute - NAFLD/MASH: weight loss, GLP-1 agonist (semaglutide, tirzepatide), pioglitazone (selected), resmetirom (FDA-approved 2024 for non-cirrhotic MASH) - Autoimmune: immunosuppression; (4) **Decompensation management**: - Ascites: sodium restriction (2 g/d) + diuretic (spironolactone + furosemide 100:40 ratio); refractory → large-volume paracentesis + albumin replacement; TIPS for refractory; - SBP prophylaxis if ascites + low protein or prior SBP — ciprofloxacin or TMP-SMX or norfloxacin daily - Hepatic encephalopathy: lactulose + rifaximin; treat precipitants - HRS: vasopressor (terlipressin, midodrine + octreotide + albumin) + RRT bridge; transplant - HPS (hepatopulmonary syndrome) — transplant evaluation; (5) **Liver transplant evaluation**: - MELD-Na score (waitlist priority US) - Refer when MELD > 15, refractory complications, HCC within criteria - Comprehensive evaluation: cardiac, pulm, infectious, psychosocial, cancer; (6) **Nutrition**: high-calorie + high-protein (1.2-1.5 g/kg); avoid restrictive low-protein (worsens malnutrition + encephalopathy); zinc, vitamin D, thiamine; (7) **Vaccinations** (inactivated): HAV, HBV, pneumococcal, influenza, COVID, Tdap; (8) **Lifestyle**: absolute alcohol cessation, smoking cessation, weight management (NAFLD), exercise; (9) **Avoid hepatotoxic medications**: NSAIDs (renal + bleeding), high-dose acetaminophen (2 g/day max in cirrhotic), aminoglycosides; (10) **Frailty + sarcopenia** — assessment + intervention

---

**Cirrhosis comprehensive management** — multidimensional. **HCC surveillance** (AASLD): US ± AFP q6 mo for cirrhosis + at-risk HBV. Sensitivity ~ 60-80% (US alone); higher with AFP. Multi-phase CT/MRI for diagnosis with LI-RADS. **Variceal surveillance** (Baveno VII): - EGD at diagnosis - Small varices no red signs: q2 yr - Medium/large or red signs: primary prophylaxis (NSBB — carvedilol preferred per recent data, or EVBL) - Secondary: NSBB + EVBL until eradication **Decompensation management**: - Ascites: Na restriction + diuretic; TIPS for refractory; albumin with LVP - SBP: prophylaxis ciprofloxacin/norfloxacin/TMP-SMX in at-risk - Encephalopathy: lactulose + rifaximin; precipitants - HRS: terlipressin + albumin; transplant - Portal HTN: TIPS for refractory complications **Transplant evaluation**: MELD-Na > 15, refractory complications, HCC within criteria. **Underlying disease specific**: HBV antiviral, HCV DAA cure, alcohol cessation, NAFLD weight loss + emerging therapies (resmetirom FDA 2024 for non-cirrhotic MASH; semaglutide promising), AIH/PBC/PSC immunosuppression. **Nutrition**: do NOT restrict protein (worsens sarcopenia + encephalopathy); 1.2-1.5 g/kg; zinc, vit D, thiamine. **Vaccinations inactivated**. **Avoid hepatotoxic**: NSAIDs, high acetaminophen, aminoglycosides. **Frailty + sarcopenia**: Liver Frailty Index (LFI); intervention.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 65 ปี chronic alcohol use + cirrhosis + esophageal varices on propranolol + EVBL + adherent — มา clinic for routine surveillance

คำถาม: HCC surveillance + cirrhosis management principles';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Antibiotic alone"},{"label":"B","text":"Prosthetic graft infection — surgical emergency requires combined antimicrobial + surgical management"},{"label":"C","text":"Outpatient management"},{"label":"D","text":"Amputation immediately"},{"label":"E","text":"Wait for resolution"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Prosthetic graft infection — surgical emergency requires combined antimicrobial + surgical management**: (1) **Vascular graft infection (early < 4 mo more severe; late >4 mo possibly less severe but chronic)**; (2) **Initial workup**: blood cultures + wound culture + tissue cultures + CT angiography (perigraft fluid/gas/abscess, anastomotic pseudoaneurysm); (3) **IV broad-spectrum antibiotic** — cover staph (incl MRSA), gram-negative — empiric vancomycin + cefepime or pip-tazo; tailor per culture; long course (6 weeks IV + 6 weeks oral suppression often; lifelong oral if cannot remove graft); (4) **Surgical management options** by severity + extent: - **Graft excision + extra-anatomic bypass** — gold standard for severe infection of prosthetic graft (e.g., axillobifemoral bypass for aortobifemoral graft infection); ''remove infection, reroute flow'' - **In-situ replacement with autologous vein** (femoral vein, GSV, cryopreserved) — for selected (lower infection burden, anatomy suitable, organism less virulent) - **In-situ replacement with new prosthetic / rifampin-soaked prosthetic** — controversial, less infection burden, soft-tissue coverage; selected - **Local debridement + irrigation + muscle flap coverage + retained graft** — selected (low-virulence, localized, no anastomosis involvement); risk of recurrence - **Suppressive antibiotic alone** — if graft cannot be safely removed (elderly, prohibitive surgery) — chronic infection accepted; (5) **Multidisciplinary**: vascular surgery, ID, plastic surgery (flaps), wound care; (6) **Limb salvage** consideration if graft removal compromises perfusion → bypass first to preserve limb then address infection; (7) **Prevention**: meticulous technique, prophylactic antibiotic, avoid groin incision when feasible (high infection rate), tunnel away from skin, treat infections elsewhere pre-op, glycemic control, smoking cessation

---

**Vascular graft infection** — 1-5% incidence; mortality 10-25%; limb loss 10-20%. **Classification**: - **Szilagyi**: I — skin only; II — subcutaneous; III — graft involvement - **Samson**: I-V — granular detail of extent - **Early (< 4 mo)**: more virulent, sepsis common, often Staph - **Late (> 4 mo)**: indolent, low-virulence organisms (coag-neg Staph), chronic sinus tract **Imaging**: - CT angiography — perigraft fluid, gas, abscess, pseudoaneurysm, aortoenteric fistula - PET-CT — infection localization (high sensitivity) - WBC scan **Management principles**: 1. **Antibiotic** — broad-spectrum + culture-directed; long duration 2. **Surgery** — usually graft removal + revascularization 3. **Extra-anatomic bypass** — definitive for severe (e.g., axillobifem for aortic graft infection) 4. **In-situ replacement** — autologous vein (femoral or GSV) or cryopreserved arterial; or rifampin-soaked prosthetic in selected 5. **Selected conservative** — debridement + flap + retain graft for low-virulence, localized **Aortoenteric fistula** — feared complication of aortic graft infection — bleed from GI tract (small hemorrhage ''herald bleed'' before catastrophic); emergency. **Prevention**: aseptic technique, antibiotic prophylaxis (cefazolin pre-incision, redose long surgery), groin avoidance when possible (high infection — alternatives like extraperitoneal access), wound closure, glycemic control, smoking cessation, MRSA decolonization in high-risk. **Long-term**: lifelong oral antibiotic suppression in selected (cannot remove graft + chronic low-grade infection); surveillance for recurrence + complications.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'ชายไทยอายุ 60 ปี ผ่า bypass graft femoropopliteal 2 weeks ago — มา ED ด้วยอาการ persistent leg swelling + pain + increasing erythema along graft site + draining wound + ไข้

VS: BP 116/72, HR 102, Temp 38.6°C
Leg: surgical wound erythema + drainage purulent; calf swollen; pulse intact distally
Lab: WBC 16,400, CRP 180
Blood culture: gram-positive cocci
CT angiogram: fluid + air around prosthetic graft; no acute occlusion; perigraft abscess

คำถาม: management';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Stop resuscitation immediately"},{"label":"B","text":"Pediatric cardiac arrest — PALS protocol with airway emphasis (often respiratory etiology in children)"},{"label":"C","text":"Discharge home"},{"label":"D","text":"Surgery alone"},{"label":"E","text":"Wait without intervention"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Pediatric cardiac arrest — PALS protocol with airway emphasis (often respiratory etiology in children)**: (1) **Most pediatric arrest is respiratory in origin** (asphyxia, drowning, choking, sepsis) — different from adult primary cardiac; (2) **Immediate steps**: - Bystander/EMS high-quality CPR (chest compressions 100-120/min, depth 1/3 AP diameter — 4 cm infant, 5 cm child, 5-6 cm adolescent) - Coordinated compressions:breaths 30:2 (single rescuer) or 15:2 (2 rescuers child) - Early effective ventilation critical - Automated external defibrillator (AED) — pediatric pads/attenuator for < 25 kg or < 8 yr (use adult if pediatric not available) - Defibrillation for shockable rhythms (VF/VT) — 2 J/kg first shock, 4 J/kg subsequent; (3) **In hospital**: - Continue compressions - Secure airway: bag-mask first (effective oxygenation often), advanced airway (ET tube, supraglottic) when feasible - IV access (peripheral or intraosseous — IO is fast + reliable in pediatric, especially when peripheral difficult) - **Epinephrine** 0.01 mg/kg IV/IO q3-5 min - **Amiodarone** 5 mg/kg IV/IO for VF/VT (after 3rd shock); lidocaine alternative - Treat reversible causes (H''s + T''s): hypoxia, hypovolemia, hydrogen ion (acidosis), hypo/hyperkalemia, hypothermia, hypoglycemia, toxins, tamponade, tension pneumo, thrombosis (PE, coronary), trauma; (4) **Post-cardiac arrest care (PALS)**: - Targeted temperature management — pediatric: maintain normothermia or therapeutic hypothermia (32-34°C × 48h then rewarm) per THAPCA pediatric trials (modest benefit/equipoise) - Oxygenation target SpO2 94-99% - Hemodynamic optimization - Neurological assessment + supportive care - Identify + treat underlying cause - Family support, psychosocial; (5) **Strangulation / hanging-specific**: - Cervical spine immobilization (potential injury) - Airway: edema common, may need surgical airway; ENT consult - CT brain + cervical spine when stable - Neuro-protective care + neurological prognostication; (6) **Outcomes**: - Pediatric in-hospital arrest survival ~ 30-50% to discharge (better than adult) - Out-of-hospital pediatric ~ 10-15% survival - Neurological outcome variable; (7) **Trauma resuscitation considerations**: TXA in massive bleeding (pediatric dose 15 mg/kg max 1 g), blood products, surgical bleeding control; (8) **Family presence** during resuscitation — supported by AHA + pediatric guidelines — improves family coping

---

**Pediatric cardiac arrest** — distinct from adult: 1. **Etiology**: respiratory most common (asphyxia, drowning, choking, sepsis, SIDS) vs adult primary cardiac (VF) 2. **Airway + ventilation early + effective** — central to pediatric resuscitation 3. **PALS** (Pediatric Advanced Life Support) — AHA algorithm **Key differences from adult ACLS**: - Compression depth: 1/3 AP diameter (4 cm infant, 5 cm child, 5-6 cm adolescent) - Compression:Ventilation ratio: 30:2 single rescuer, 15:2 two rescuers (child); adult always 30:2 - Defibrillation: 2 J/kg first, 4 J/kg subsequent; pediatric pads/attenuator < 25 kg if available - Drug dosing weight-based - Epinephrine 0.01 mg/kg IV/IO - Amiodarone 5 mg/kg IV/IO for VF/VT - IO access common (fast, reliable, equivalent to IV) **H''s + T''s** (reversible causes): hypoxia, hypovolemia, hydrogen (acidosis), hypo/hyperkalemia, hypothermia, hypoglycemia, toxins, tamponade, tension pneumothorax, thrombosis (PE, coronary), trauma. **Post-arrest care (PALS)**: - Targeted temperature management — pediatric: THAPCA trials show no clear benefit of hypothermia 32-34°C vs normothermia 36-37.5°C; either acceptable - Avoid hyperthermia (fever post-arrest worsens outcomes) - Oxygen target 94-99% (avoid hyperoxia) - Hemodynamic, neurological support **Strangulation/hanging-specific considerations**: cervical spine injury, airway edema (may need surgical airway), CT imaging, neuroprotective care. **Trauma**: TXA (15 mg/kg max 1 g pediatric), blood products, surgical control. **Family presence during resuscitation**: increasingly supported (AHA, pediatric guidelines) — improves family coping + closure. **Outcomes**: pediatric in-hospital arrest ~ 30-50% survival to discharge (better than adult); out-of-hospital ~ 10-15%. Variable neurological outcome — depends on cause, downtime, witnessed status, bystander CPR.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'เด็กชายอายุ 3 ปี ผ้าปูเตียงพันคอเล่นกัน — ตื่นมาภาวะสุดเย็น ครอบครัวพบในห้องไม่ตอบสนอง + นำส่ง ER

VS: not breathing, pulseless, asystole on monitor
Family started CPR + 911 — ETA 8 min

คำถาม: pediatric cardiac arrest + resuscitation';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Rejection cannot be prevented"},{"label":"B","text":"Transplant rejection mechanisms + immunosuppression"},{"label":"C","text":"No immunosuppression needed"},{"label":"D","text":"Single agent for life"},{"label":"E","text":"Cure tolerance achievable for all"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Transplant rejection mechanisms + immunosuppression**: (1) **Types of rejection**: - **Hyperacute** (minutes-hours): preformed antibodies (ABO incompatibility, HLA mismatch) → complement + thrombosis; modern era rare (crossmatch screening); treatment: graft removal - **Acute cellular (T-cell mediated)**: days-weeks; T-cells recognize donor MHC; treatable with steroid + ATG; tubulitis + interstitial infiltrate (kidney) - **Acute antibody-mediated (AMR)**: B-cell + antibody mediated; weeks-months; C4d deposition + DSA; harder treatment (plasmapheresis + IVIG + rituximab + bortezomib) - **Chronic rejection** (months-years): combined immune + non-immune; obliterative arteriopathy, fibrosis; harder to reverse; gradual graft dysfunction; (2) **HLA + immune recognition**: - HLA Class I (A, B, C) — most cells - HLA Class II (DR, DQ, DP) — antigen-presenting cells - Direct + indirect alloantigen recognition - Crossmatch testing (CDC + flow + virtual) pre-transplant essential - DSA (donor-specific antibodies) — risk of AMR; (3) **Immunosuppression categories**: a. **Induction** (peri-transplant): - **Antibody therapy**: anti-thymocyte globulin (ATG — polyclonal T-cell depleting), basiliximab (anti-IL-2 receptor), alemtuzumab (anti-CD52, more depleting) - **Steroid bolus**: methylprednisolone b. **Maintenance** (lifelong): - **Calcineurin inhibitors (CNI)**: tacrolimus, cyclosporine — backbone; nephrotoxicity major side effect - **Antimetabolites**: mycophenolate (MMF, MPA) > azathioprine - **Steroids**: prednisone (often tapered to low-dose or stopped) - **mTOR inhibitors**: sirolimus, everolimus — anti-tumor; SE: poor wound healing, pneumonitis, mouth ulcers, hyperlipidemia - **Costimulation blockade**: belatacept (CD80/86) c. **Rejection treatment**: - Acute cellular: pulse steroid + ATG - AMR: plasmapheresis + IVIG + rituximab + bortezomib/daratumumab - Refractory: alemtuzumab; (4) **Side effects of immunosuppression** to manage: - Infection (opportunistic — CMV, PJP, fungal; bacterial; reactivation HBV) - Malignancy (skin, PTLD, increased cancer risk overall) - Cardiovascular (HT, hyperlipidemia, DM) - Renal (CNI nephrotoxicity) - Neurological (tremor, headache, CNI neurotoxicity, PRES) - Hematologic (cytopenias) - Metabolic (NODAT — new-onset DM after transplant) - Bone (osteoporosis from steroid); (5) **Therapeutic drug monitoring**: tacrolimus, cyclosporine, sirolimus, mycophenolate levels; (6) **Tolerance** — holy grail: mixed chimerism, regulatory T cells, donor BM transplant + organ — experimental; clinical trials ongoing; (7) **Long-term**: cancer surveillance, infection prophylaxis, cardiovascular risk, drug interactions awareness; adherence support

---

**Transplant immunology + immunosuppression** — foundational. **Types of rejection**: 1. **Hyperacute**: minutes-hours; preformed Ab; ABO + HLA mismatch; thrombosis; graft loss — prevented by crossmatch 2. **Acute cellular (TCMR)**: T-cell mediated; days-months; treatable with pulse steroid 3. **Acute antibody-mediated (AMR)**: B-cell + Ab; days-months; harder treatment (PEX, IVIG, rituximab) 4. **Chronic**: months-years; multifactorial; gradual graft loss **HLA Class I (A, B, C)** all nucleated cells. **HLA Class II (DR, DQ, DP)** APCs (B cells, macrophages, dendritic). **Alloantigen recognition**: direct (donor APC presenting donor HLA to recipient T cell) + indirect (recipient APC processing donor antigen). **Pre-transplant testing**: ABO, HLA, PRA (panel reactive antibodies), crossmatch (CDC, flow, virtual), DSA assessment. **Immunosuppression — 3 phases**: 1. **Induction** (peri-op): - ATG (T-cell depleting, polyclonal) - Basiliximab (anti-IL2R, less depleting) - Alemtuzumab (anti-CD52, profound depletion) - Methylprednisolone bolus 2. **Maintenance** (lifelong, ''triple therapy'' common): - CNI (tacrolimus > cyclosporine) — backbone - Antiproliferative (mycophenolate > azathioprine) - Steroid (prednisone — often tapered) - Alternatives: mTOR inhibitor (sirolimus, everolimus), belatacept 3. **Rejection treatment**: - Acute cellular: pulse steroid + ATG - AMR: plasmapheresis + IVIG + rituximab ± bortezomib + steroids **Side effect profile** (major considerations): - Tacrolimus: nephrotoxic, neurotoxic, NODAT, HT, tremor, hair loss, hyperK - Cyclosporine: similar + hirsutism, gum hyperplasia - Mycophenolate: GI, leukopenia, anemia, teratogenic - Sirolimus: wound healing impaired, pneumonitis, hyperlipidemia, mouth ulcers - Steroids: HT, DM, osteoporosis, cataract, weight, mood, AVN - Belatacept: PTLD risk (especially EBV-naive recipient) **Therapeutic drug monitoring**: trough levels (tacrolimus, cyclosporine, sirolimus, everolimus); higher targets early post-transplant, lower later. **Tolerance** — operational tolerance without immunosuppression: holy grail; mixed chimerism (Stanford, Mass Gen + others) achieving partial success in selected; not clinical routine yet.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'Basic science: immunology + transplant

คำถาม: organ rejection mechanisms + immunosuppression';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Cancer is always sporadic"},{"label":"B","text":"Hereditary cancer syndromes — surgical implications"},{"label":"C","text":"No screening needed"},{"label":"D","text":"Surgery always avoided"},{"label":"E","text":"Single approach for all"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Hereditary cancer syndromes — surgical implications**: (1) **HBOC (Hereditary Breast Ovarian Cancer) — BRCA1/2**: - Lifetime breast cancer 45-72% (BRCA1) / 45-69% (BRCA2); ovarian 39-44% / 11-17% - Risk-reducing mastectomy (RRM) — reduces breast Ca 90%+ - Risk-reducing salpingo-oophorectomy (RRSO) — at 35-40 (BRCA1) / 40-45 (BRCA2) after childbearing; reduces ovarian Ca > 80% + breast Ca ~ 50% (if premenopausal) - PARP inhibitors (olaparib, talazoparib) — adjuvant high-risk + metastatic - Increased pancreatic + prostate (BRCA2 esp), male breast (BRCA2), melanoma (BRCA2); (2) **Lynch Syndrome (HNPCC) — MLH1, MSH2, MSH6, PMS2, EPCAM**: - Colorectal lifetime 50-80% - Endometrial 40-60%, ovarian, gastric, small bowel, urothelial, brain, sebaceous skin (Muir-Torre) - Surveillance: colonoscopy q1-2 yr from 20-25; gynecologic surveillance; consider prophylactic hysterectomy + BSO after childbearing - Total colectomy with IRA if cancer diagnosed (synchronous + metachronous risk) - Immunotherapy (anti-PD-1 — pembrolizumab) for MSI-H/dMMR cancers — striking responses; (3) **FAP (Familial Adenomatous Polyposis) — APC gene**: - Colorectal cancer near 100% if untreated by 35-45 - Prophylactic total colectomy (with IRA — ileorectal anastomosis) or proctocolectomy with IPAA - Duodenal adenoma + cancer surveillance (EGD with side-viewer) - Desmoid tumor risk (especially attenuated FAP) - Thyroid Ca, brain tumor (Turcot variant), hepatoblastoma, osteoma, fibroma; (4) **MEN1 (Menin)**: - Parathyroid (primary HPT) - Pituitary adenoma - Pancreatic neuroendocrine (gastrinoma, insulinoma, others) - Adrenal, foregut carcinoid - Genetic counseling + screening - Parathyroidectomy + pancreaticoduodenectomy timing case-by-case; (5) **MEN2 (RET)**: - **MEN2A**: medullary thyroid Ca (MTC) + pheochromocytoma + parathyroid - **MEN2B**: MTC + pheo + mucosal neuromas, marfanoid - **Familial MTC** only - Prophylactic thyroidectomy in MEN2A by 5 yr, MEN2B by 1 yr - Pheochromocytoma screening lifelong; (6) **VHL (Von Hippel-Lindau)**: clear cell renal carcinoma, hemangioblastoma (CNS, retina), pheochromocytoma, pancreatic NET, endolymphatic sac tumor — multi-system surveillance + intervention; (7) **NF1 (Neurofibromatosis 1)**: neurofibromas, MPNST risk, pheochromocytoma, optic glioma, etc.; (8) **NF2**: vestibular schwannomas bilateral, meningioma; (9) **TP53 (Li-Fraumeni)**: sarcoma, breast, brain, adrenocortical, leukemia — multi-cancer; intensive surveillance (whole-body MRI); (10) **CDH1 (Hereditary Diffuse Gastric Ca)**: gastric (diffuse-type) + lobular breast — prophylactic total gastrectomy considered + breast surveillance/RRM; (11) **PTEN (Cowden)**: breast, thyroid, endometrial, renal, colon, melanoma — surveillance + selective intervention; (12) **STK11 (Peutz-Jeghers)**: GI hamartomatous polyps, breast, ovarian, pancreatic, cervical Ca; (13) **Genetic counseling + cascade testing of family** — essential

---

**Hereditary cancer syndromes** — ~ 5-10% of all cancers; genetic testing increasingly accessible (NGS multi-gene panels). Each syndrome has specific cancer profile + surveillance + risk-reduction options. **NCCN Guidelines for Genetic/Familial High-Risk Assessment** — detailed criteria for testing. Increasingly: ''all-comer'' testing in certain cancers (pancreatic, ovarian, triple-negative breast, prostate metastatic) regardless of family history. **Major syndromes** (described above) — surgical implications: 1. **HBOC** (BRCA1/2): RRM, RRSO 2. **Lynch**: extensive colon resection if cancer; prophylactic hysterectomy + BSO after childbearing; intensive surveillance 3. **FAP**: prophylactic colectomy mandatory by 20s; subtotal with IRA vs total proctocolectomy + IPAA; duodenal surveillance 4. **MEN1**: pancreatic + parathyroid surgery timing 5. **MEN2**: prophylactic thyroidectomy in childhood; pheo workup before any surgery 6. **CDH1**: prophylactic total gastrectomy considered; breast surveillance/RRM 7. **VHL**: intervention for selected RCCs (nephron-sparing), hemangioblastoma, pheo 8. **Li-Fraumeni**: cancer-by-cancer; intensive surveillance whole-body MRI **Genetic counseling principles**: - Pre-test counseling: implications, limitations, alternatives - Variant interpretation (pathogenic, likely pathogenic, VUS, benign) — VUS management challenging - Cascade testing of family — important for risk stratification - Reproductive options (PGT — preimplantation genetic testing) - Psychosocial + insurance considerations (GINA US protects against insurance discrimination — health, not life or long-term care) **Polygenic risk scores (PRS)** — emerging for common cancers; combines multiple low-penetrance SNPs; may augment surveillance decisions; not standard yet. **Multi-gene panel testing** — practical efficiency vs single-gene; identifies syndromes beyond what''s clinically suspected; manage incidental findings.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'Basic science: medical genetics + hereditary cancer syndromes

คำถาม: hereditary cancer syndromes + surgical implications';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Anatomy not relevant"},{"label":"B","text":"Abdominal wall anatomy + hernia types"},{"label":"C","text":"All hernias same management"},{"label":"D","text":"No anatomy review needed"},{"label":"E","text":"Children always need mesh"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Abdominal wall anatomy + hernia types**: (1) **Layers** (outside to inside): skin, subcutaneous (Camper''s fascia + Scarpa''s fascia), external oblique aponeurosis, internal oblique, transversus abdominis, transversalis fascia, peritoneum; (2) **Rectus abdominis sheath**: above arcuate line — anterior (EO + ½ IO) + posterior (½ IO + TA); below arcuate line — all anterior (rectus directly on transversalis fascia + peritoneum) — explains lower abdominal hernias predilection; (3) **Linea alba** midline fibrous raphe; **linea semilunaris** lateral border of rectus; **arcuate line (semicircular line of Douglas)** ~ midway between umbilicus + pubis; (4) **Inguinal canal anatomy**: - Floor (posterior wall): transversalis fascia + conjoint tendon (medial) - Roof: internal oblique + transversus abdominis (conjoint) - Anterior: external oblique aponeurosis - Posterior: transversalis - Contents: spermatic cord (M) / round ligament (F) - **Hesselbach''s triangle**: medial — rectus, inferior — inguinal ligament, lateral — inferior epigastric vessels; (5) **Hernias — definitions**: - **Reducible**: contents return to abdomen - **Incarcerated**: stuck, irreducible, no ischemia - **Strangulated**: ischemic, surgical emergency - **Sliding**: part of sac is wall of viscus; (6) **Types of abdominal wall hernias**: a. **Inguinal**: - Indirect (lateral to inferior epigastric vessels — through deep ring, follows spermatic cord) — congenital patent processus vaginalis; common in pediatric + young adult - Direct (medial, through Hesselbach''s triangle) — acquired weakness; older - Femoral (below inguinal ligament, through femoral canal) — more in women; high incarceration risk → repair upon diagnosis b. **Umbilical** — congenital in children (usually closes by 5 yr); acquired in adults (pregnancy, obesity, ascites); repair if symptomatic or > 1-1.5 cm c. **Epigastric** — midline above umbilicus through linea alba defect; small fat-only often; repair if symptomatic d. **Spigelian** — at semilunar line below arcuate line; rare; high incarceration risk → repair e. **Lumbar** (Petit, Grynfeltt triangles) — rare; congenital or acquired f. **Incisional** — through prior surgical scar (10-20% of laparotomies); repair with mesh; component separation for large defects g. **Parastomal** — adjacent to stoma; common; complex repair h. **Perineal** — through pelvic floor; post-pelvic surgery or rare congenital i. **Internal hernias** (e.g., Petersen''s post-RYGB) — no abdominal wall defect, mesenteric defect inside; (7) **Surgical principles**: - Repair indication: symptomatic, complications, asymptomatic for incarceration-prone (femoral, Spigelian) - Mesh > primary suture in adults for lower recurrence - Pediatric: high ligation, NO mesh - Approach: open (Lichtenstein) vs laparoscopic (TEP, TAPP); robotic; - Component separation (anterior — Ramirez; posterior — TAR transversus abdominis release) for large complex ventral hernias - Mesh placement: onlay, sublay (preferred for ventral — retro-rectus), inlay (rare), preperitoneal/TEP (inguinal)

---

**Abdominal wall anatomy + hernias** — surgical staple. Foundation: anatomic layers (skin → subQ → muscles + aponeuroses → transversalis fascia → peritoneum). Key structures: rectus sheath (varies above/below arcuate line), inguinal canal, linea alba, linea semilunaris, Hesselbach''s triangle. **Hernia types**: 1. **Inguinal** (most common): indirect (lateral to epigastric vessels), direct (medial, Hesselbach), femoral (below inguinal ligament — repair always, high incarceration) 2. **Umbilical** (children + adults) 3. **Epigastric** (midline above umbilicus) 4. **Spigelian** (semilunar line — high incarceration) 5. **Lumbar** (rare) 6. **Incisional** (10-20% post-laparotomy) 7. **Parastomal** (adjacent to stoma) 8. **Perineal** 9. **Internal hernias** (mesenteric defects, e.g., post-RYGB Petersen''s) **Surgical approaches**: - **Open Lichtenstein** (tension-free mesh) — gold standard inguinal - **Laparoscopic TEP** (totally extraperitoneal) or **TAPP** (transabdominal preperitoneal) — equal/better outcomes (chronic pain, bilateral repair, recurrent); lower learning curve - **Robotic** — increasing - **Component separation** (anterior Ramirez, posterior TAR) — for large complex ventral - **Mesh placement options**: onlay (top), sublay/retromuscular (preferred), inlay (rare), preperitoneal **Modern principles**: - Tension-free mesh for adult primary + incisional (lower recurrence) - Light-weight mesh — less chronic pain - Bioprosthetic (Strattice, biological) — contaminated field selectively - Avoid mesh in pediatric (growth) - Watchful waiting acceptable for asymptomatic minimally symptomatic inguinal in elderly (Fitzgibbons RCT) - Repair always for femoral, Spigelian (high incarceration) **Complications**: chronic pain (10-15%), recurrence (1-5%), seroma, infection, mesh complications (migration, erosion, infection, fistula). **Quality measures**: AHSQC (Americas Hernia Society Quality Collaborative), EHS standards.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'Basic science: surgical anatomy — abdominal wall + hernias

คำถาม: abdominal wall anatomy + hernia classification';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Continue all medications"},{"label":"B","text":"Perioperative medication management — specific decisions"},{"label":"C","text":"Stop all medications 4 weeks before"},{"label":"D","text":"Start all medications day of surgery"},{"label":"E","text":"No medication review needed"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Perioperative medication management — specific decisions**: (1) **Antihypertensives**: - **ACE-I / ARB**: HOLD on day of surgery — intraoperative hypotension; resume post-op when hemodynamically stable - **Beta-blocker**: CONTINUE if chronic; DO NOT initiate new (POISE — increased death + stroke) - **Calcium channel blocker**: continue - **Diuretic**: hold day of surgery typically (volume + electrolyte) - **Clonidine** (α2-agonist): continue (withdrawal rebound HTN); (2) **Antidiabetic**: - **Metformin**: usually OK day before; hold day of surgery for major (lactic acidosis risk if CKD); - **Sulfonylureas**: hold day of surgery (hypoglycemia) - **SGLT2 inhibitor (canagliflozin, empagliflozin, dapagliflozin)**: HOLD 3-4 days pre-op (DKA risk — euglycemic DKA can occur with normal glucose; FDA warning) - **GLP-1 (semaglutide, liraglutide, tirzepatide)**: HOLD 1 week pre-op for daily, 2 weeks for weekly (delayed gastric emptying → aspiration risk during anesthesia — ASA + ASRA guidance 2023) - **DPP-4 inhibitor (sitagliptin)**: usually continue - **Insulin**: long-acting reduced dose night before + day of, short-acting hold day of, sliding scale + correction; (3) **Anticoagulant + antiplatelet**: see prior question on perioperative anticoagulation; (4) **Statin**: CONTINUE — perioperative cardiovascular protection; (5) **Hormonal**: - **OCP, HRT**: VTE risk — consider holding 4 weeks pre-op for major + immobilization vs continuing in lower-risk - **Tamoxifen, AI**: continue (long half-life, low impact); - **GnRH agonist**: continue; (6) **Psychiatric**: - **SSRIs**: continue (rebound depression); some bleeding risk - **SNRIs**: continue - **MAOIs**: HOLD 2 weeks pre-op if possible (severe drug interaction with sympathomimetics, meperidine, opioid) - **TCAs**: continue typically - **Lithium**: hold day of surgery + monitor electrolyte (renal); - **Antipsychotics**: continue (avoid withdrawal); (7) **Antiepileptics**: continue (perioperative seizure prevention); IV equivalent if NPO; (8) **Immunosuppressants** (transplant, autoimmune): continue (avoid rejection / flare); stress-dose steroid if chronic; (9) **Steroids**: - Stress dose if HPA suppression suspected (chronic ≥ 20 mg prednisone or equivalent × 3 weeks within last year — debated, modern less aggressive per Marik) - Continue or supplement during surgery + post-op taper; (10) **Herbal supplements**: - Hold 1-2 weeks pre-op: ginkgo, garlic, ginseng, ginger (bleeding); St. John''s wort (drug interactions); kava, valerian (sedation); ephedra (sympathomimetic - banned); echinacea (immune modulation); (11) **NSAIDs**: hold 5-7 days pre-op for elective; aspirin individualized; (12) **Antiretrovirals (HIV)**: continue (avoid resistance); coordinate with ID + pharmacist for drug interactions; (13) **Opioids** (chronic use, addiction recovery): continue baseline + multimodal adjuncts; addiction medicine consult; (14) **Pre-op assessment + medication reconciliation** essential; pharmacist consultation in complex polypharmacy

---

**Perioperative medication management** — common source of errors; impacts outcomes. **Categories** (continue, hold, modify): 1. **HOLD** day of surgery: ACE-I/ARB, sulfonylureas, SGLT2, GLP-1 (1-2 weeks), diuretics (variable), most NSAIDs (elective), warfarin (5 days), DOACs (1-2 days based on procedure), oral hypoglycemics (mostly day of) 2. **CONTINUE** through surgery: beta-blocker (if chronic), statin, ACE-I/ARB sometimes for HF (newer evidence — controversy), SSRIs, antiepileptics, antipsychotics, immunosuppressants, antiretrovirals, calcium channel blockers, antiparkinsonian (don''t withdraw — worsening symptoms) 3. **MODIFY**: insulin (reduce long-acting + hold short-acting + sliding scale day of), steroids (stress dose if HPA-suppressed) **Key specifics — recent updates**: - **SGLT2 inhibitors**: HOLD 3-4 days pre-op due to euglycemic DKA risk (FDA warning + clinical case series) - **GLP-1 agonists**: HOLD 1 week for daily formulations, 2 weeks for weekly (semaglutide, dulaglutide, tirzepatide) due to delayed gastric emptying + aspiration risk (ASA + ASRA 2023 guidance) - **Beta-blocker**: continue if chronic; DO NOT INITIATE NEW perioperatively (POISE trial NEJM 2008 — increased death + stroke) - **Aspirin**: continue except for high-bleed surgery (intracranial, posterior chamber eye, transurethral prostate); POISE-2 supported continuation generally **Steroid stress dose**: traditional approach for chronic ≥ 20 mg prednisone or equivalent × 3 weeks within last year — debated; modern approach: hydrocortisone 50-100 mg pre-op + post-op taper; some prefer simpler ''continue usual dose'' approach with monitoring (Marik + others suggested over-treatment historically). **Herbal supplements**: many affect bleeding (gingko, garlic, ginseng, ginger), sedation (kava, valerian), HPA (ginseng, licorice), drug interactions (St. John''s wort) — hold 1-2 weeks pre-op. **Anesthesia + drug interactions**: MAOI + sympathomimetic + meperidine (serotonin syndrome) — hold MAOI 2 weeks if possible; antiretroviral + opioid metabolism considerations; pharmacist consultation for polypharmacy. **Reconciliation** at admission + discharge — important to prevent omission + duplication. **Patient education** — clear instructions for what to take/not take morning of surgery.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'Basic science: surgical pharmacology + drug interactions

คำถาม: perioperative medication management';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No systematic approach needed"},{"label":"B","text":"ATLS (Advanced Trauma Life Support) — systematic approach"},{"label":"C","text":"Random workup"},{"label":"D","text":"Discharge all trauma"},{"label":"E","text":"Single specialty only"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **ATLS (Advanced Trauma Life Support) — systematic approach**: (1) **Pre-arrival**: communication with EMS, team activation, prepare equipment, blood products, OR notification; (2) **Primary survey ABCDE — identify + treat life-threats simultaneously**: - **A — Airway** with cervical spine protection: assess patency, talking = patent; obstructed → jaw thrust, suction, oral/nasal airway, supraglottic, intubation (rapid sequence with C-spine inline immobilization), surgical airway last resort; - **B — Breathing**: inspect, palpate, percuss, auscultate; identify life-threats: tension pneumothorax (needle/finger decompression — 5th ICS anterior axillary), open pneumothorax (3-sided occlusive dressing), massive hemothorax (chest tube > 1.5L initial OR > 200 mL/hr × 4h → OR), flail chest (positive pressure ventilation if respiratory failure); - **C — Circulation** + hemorrhage control: assess pulse, capillary refill, mental status, BP; identify hemorrhage sources: external (direct pressure, tourniquet, hemostatic gauze), thoracic (chest tube), abdominal (FAST), pelvic (binder + angio + REBOA), retroperitoneal, long bone fractures (splinting + ortho); 2 large-bore IV (16-18g) or IO; type & cross; balanced resuscitation (1:1:1 PRC:FFP:Plt early in massive bleed per PROPPR); permissive hypotension (no TBI); TXA early (CRASH-2 + CRASH-3); MTP activation; calcium (citrate binding) - **D — Disability**: GCS (E4V5M6 = 15), pupil (size + reactivity), gross motor; head trauma signs - **E — Exposure + environmental**: completely undress, log roll, look for occult injuries (back, axilla, perineum); rewarm aggressively (hypothermia worsens coagulopathy + acidosis = lethal triad); avoid cold IV fluid; (3) **Adjuncts to primary survey**: FAST exam (or eFAST including lung), CXR, pelvis XR, ECG, ABG, lactate, type + cross, urinary catheter (if no urethral injury — blood at meatus, high-riding prostate), NG/OG; (4) **Reassess + identify undiagnosed life threats**; (5) **Secondary survey** — head-to-toe systematic exam + AMPLE history (Allergies, Medications, Past, Last meal, Events); only after primary stabilized; identify all injuries — log roll + back exam, head + maxillofacial, neck + C-spine, chest, abdomen + pelvis, perineum + rectal, musculoskeletal, neurological detailed; (6) **Definitive care + transfer** — to appropriate trauma center if needed; do NOT delay definitive care for prolonged workup; OR + IR + ICU coordination; (7) **Tertiary survey** — within 24h, identifies missed injuries (5-10% miss rate without tertiary); (8) **Special populations**: - **Pediatric**: weight-based dosing, anatomical differences, vital sign norms differ, NAT consideration - **Geriatric**: under-triage common due to compensated initial vitals; lower threshold for trauma center - **Pregnant**: maternal first (best for fetus); left lateral tilt (avoid IVC compression > 20 weeks); fetal monitoring; Rh status (Rhogam) - **Anticoagulated**: reversal (PCC, TXA, FFP); reverse first then evaluate; (9) **Damage control resuscitation (DCR) + damage control surgery (DCS)** principles when severely injured; (10) **Communication + handoff** structured (SBAR); patient + family disclosure

---

**ATLS** — global standard for trauma initial evaluation + management. Systematic ABCDE primary survey identifies + treats life threats simultaneously; secondary survey for complete injury identification; tertiary survey within 24h for missed injuries (5-10% miss rate). **Primary survey life-threats**: - **Airway**: obstruction → maneuvers → airway adjuncts → intubation → surgical airway - **Breathing**: tension pneumothorax (decompress), open pneumothorax (3-sided dressing + chest tube), massive hemothorax (chest tube; > 1500 mL or > 200 mL/h × 4h → OR), flail chest (PPV if respiratory failure), cardiac tamponade (pericardiocentesis + thoracotomy) - **Circulation**: external bleeding control (pressure, tourniquet, hemostatic), source identification (FAST, CXR, pelvis), IV access (2 large bore), balanced resuscitation, TXA, MTP, calcium - **Disability**: GCS, pupils, gross motor - **Exposure**: undress, log roll, rewarm **Adjuncts**: FAST/eFAST, CXR, pelvis, ECG, ABG, lactate, type + cross, Foley (if no urethral injury), NG. **Pelvic binder** for unstable pelvic fracture before any imaging — temporizes hemorrhage. **REBOA** (Resuscitative Endovascular Balloon Occlusion of Aorta) — emerging adjunct for non-compressible torso hemorrhage in extremis — Zone 1 (above diaphragm) or Zone 3 (below renal); bridge to definitive control. **Damage control resuscitation (DCR)**: balanced products 1:1:1 (PROPPR), permissive hypotension (no TBI), TXA early (CRASH-2 NEJM 2010 within 3h; CRASH-3 NEJM 2019 within 3h of mild-moderate TBI), avoid lethal triad (coagulopathy + hypothermia + acidosis), calcium replacement. **Damage control surgery (DCS)**: abbreviated initial operation — control hemorrhage + contamination, temporary closure → ICU resuscitation → definitive 24-48h. **Trauma center matters**: outcomes 20-25% better in dedicated trauma centers (MacKenzie NEJM 2006). **Special populations**: pediatric (weight-based, family centered), geriatric (under-triage risk, anticoagulation, lower threshold to trauma center, modified Frailty Index), pregnant (resuscitate mom first, left lateral tilt, Rh status), anticoagulated (reverse early).'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'Basic science: trauma evaluation — primary + secondary survey

คำถาม: ATLS principles + trauma evaluation';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No nutrition needed in ICU"},{"label":"B","text":"Critical Care Nutrition (ASPEN/SCCM Guidelines)"},{"label":"C","text":"TPN for all"},{"label":"D","text":"NPO indefinitely"},{"label":"E","text":"Single formula for all patients"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Critical Care Nutrition (ASPEN/SCCM Guidelines)**: (1) **Initiation timing**: - **Early enteral nutrition (EN) within 24-48h** of ICU admission if hemodynamically stable + no contraindication - **Parenteral nutrition (PN)** only if EN contraindicated / insufficient ≥ 7 days (no benefit + harm with early PN — EPaNIC trial); (2) **Routes**: - **EN**: NG, NJ (post-pyloric — useful in gastroparesis, high aspiration risk, pancreatitis), gastrostomy, jejunostomy - **PN**: central (peripheral if short-term + low osmolarity); (3) **Caloric target**: - Early phase (acute, days 1-3): permissive underfeeding 50-70% (recent evidence — full feeds may worsen outcomes by overfeeding stressed metabolism) - Late phase: full feeds 25-30 kcal/kg/day; - Indirect calorimetry gold standard if available - Avoid hyperglycemia + overfeeding-associated complications (hepatic steatosis, hypertriglyceridemia, CO2 retention); (4) **Protein**: higher need in critical illness — 1.2-1.5 g/kg/day (up to 2 g/kg in burns, multi-trauma, CRRT) — preserve lean body mass; (5) **Composition**: - Carb: 40-60% of calories - Fat: 25-30% (including essential FA — linoleic, α-linolenic) - Standard polymeric formulas — most patients - Specialty: - High-protein - Concentrated (fluid restriction) - Fiber-containing - Renal-specific (low K, PO4, fluid) - Immunonutrition (arginine, omega-3 PUFA, RNA nucleotides — Impact, Oxepa) — selected (elective major GI cancer surgery shows benefit; mixed in critical care — controversial in sepsis); (6) **Electrolyte management**: monitor + adjust (Na, K, PO4, Mg) — refeeding syndrome prevention; (7) **Micronutrients + vitamins**: thiamine (especially before glucose load), vitamin D + others as deficient; selenium, zinc; antioxidants — RCT evidence mixed; (8) **Glycemic control**: target 140-180; avoid hyper + hypoglycemia (NICE-SUGAR — strict glycemic control 80-110 increased mortality); (9) **Gastric residual volumes (GRV)** — historically used to assess tolerance; recent evidence: NOT necessary for routine EN tolerance check (REGANE trial — outcomes not different with vs without GRV monitoring); promotility (metoclopramide, erythromycin short-term) if intolerance; (10) **Aspiration prevention**: head of bed 30-45°, postpyloric feeding if at risk, ETT cuff pressure adequate, monitor for high gastric residuals selectively; (11) **Constipation**: laxatives, prokinetics, bowel regimen; (12) **Refeeding syndrome**: severely malnourished — phosphate, K, Mg drops + thiamine deficiency → cardiac + neurological dysfunction; prevent: slow advancement + thiamine + electrolyte replacement; (13) **Special populations**: - Burns: hypermetabolic; high protein + calorie - Trauma: aggressive nutrition - Sepsis: early enteral, hypocaloric early phase - AKI/CRRT: protein loss higher with CRRT (1.5-2.5 g/kg) - Liver failure: balanced (don''t restrict protein) - Pancreatitis: early enteral (NJ tube past leak); reduces complications + mortality - Obesity: hypocaloric, high protein (1.5-2 g/kg ideal body weight); (14) **Discharge transition**: oral intake, oral supplements, home tube feeding, home TPN if needed; outpatient nutritional follow-up

---

**Critical Care Nutrition (ASPEN/SCCM 2016 Guidelines + updates)** — important but historically under-prioritized. **Principles**: 1. **Early enteral nutrition (EN)** within 24-48h of ICU admission if stable + no contraindication — preserves gut barrier, reduces translocation, immune function, infection 2. **Parenteral nutrition (PN)** — only if EN insufficient/contraindicated ≥ 7 days; EPaNIC trial (NEJM 2011) showed early PN harmful (over-feeding, infection); 3. **Caloric target**: phase-dependent — early hypocaloric, advance later 4. **Protein target**: higher (1.2-1.5 g/kg, up to 2 g/kg in burns/CRRT) — preserve lean body mass during catabolic state 5. **Glycemic control**: 140-180 (NICE-SUGAR — strict harmful) 6. **Gastric residual volumes**: not routinely needed (REGANE) 7. **Aspiration prevention**: HOB 30-45°, postpyloric for high-risk **Specialty considerations**: - Pancreatitis: early enteral (PYTHON trial NEJM 2014; EarlyNJ studies) — reduces complications - Burns: hypermetabolic — high protein + calorie - Sepsis: early enteral, hypocaloric early - Obesity: hypocaloric + high protein per ideal body weight - Renal: protein NOT restricted in CRRT (high loss); restrict K, PO4 per renal function - Liver: don''t restrict protein; balanced **Refeeding syndrome**: in severely malnourished resuming nutrition → cells uptake K, Mg, PO4 + thiamine deficiency → cardiac arrhythmia, respiratory failure, neurologic; prevention: slow advance + thiamine pre-feed + monitor electrolytes + replace. **Immunonutrition** (arginine, ω-3 PUFA, nucleotides): - Elective major GI cancer surgery — benefit (Drover meta-analysis Ann Surg) - Critical illness/sepsis — controversial; some signal harm with arginine in septic shock; case-by-case **Glutamine** supplementation in ICU — REDOXS (NEJM 2013) showed harm with high-dose IV glutamine — discontinue routine use. **Selenium + antioxidants** — mixed evidence in critical care; not routine. **Indirect calorimetry** — gold standard for energy expenditure measurement when available + feasible; predictive equations (Harris-Benedict, Mifflin, ASPEN) widely used. **Discharge transition**: oral intake assessment, oral supplements, home tube feeding, home TPN if indicated; outpatient nutrition follow-up.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'Basic science: ICU + nutritional support

คำถาม: critical care nutrition principles';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Use broadest antibiotic always"},{"label":"B","text":"Antimicrobial Stewardship — surgical perspective"},{"label":"C","text":"No oversight needed"},{"label":"D","text":"Same antibiotic for all infections"},{"label":"E","text":"Avoid culture-directed therapy"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Antimicrobial Stewardship — surgical perspective**: (1) **Why stewardship**: - Resistance increasing globally (WHO priority — top 10 health threats) - C. difficile infection (antibiotic exposure major risk) - Cost - Pharmacy + ID team integration; (2) **Stewardship principles**: a. **Right drug, right dose, right duration**: - Narrow spectrum when organism known - Broad-spectrum empirically when severe + then de-escalate per culture - Dose for site (some abscesses need high dose) + patient (renal, hepatic, weight) - Shortest effective duration b. **De-escalation** when culture + sensitivity available c. **Source control** — surgical, percutaneous drainage, removal of infected device d. **Pharmacokinetic / pharmacodynamic considerations**: - Time-dependent (β-lactams): time above MIC critical — extended infusion or continuous - Concentration-dependent (aminoglycoside, fluoroquinolone): peak/MIC ratio - AUC/MIC (vancomycin, linezolid); (3) **Common resistant organisms in surgical patients**: a. **MRSA** (Methicillin-Resistant Staph aureus): - SSI, IV catheter infections, pneumonia - Vancomycin, daptomycin, linezolid, ceftaroline, tedizolid - Decolonization protocols (mupirocin nasal + chlorhexidine bath) reduces SSI b. **VRE** (Vancomycin-Resistant Enterococcus): - Less virulent typically but limited options - Linezolid, daptomycin, tigecycline c. **ESBL-producers** (Extended-Spectrum β-Lactamase) — E. coli, Klebsiella: - Resist most cephalosporins + penicillins - Carbapenems (meropenem, ertapenem, imipenem), pip-tazo (selected), ceftolozane-tazobactam, ceftazidime-avibactam d. **CRE / CPE** (Carbapenem-Resistant Enterobacterales, Carbapenemase-Producing Enterobacterales): - Limited options: ceftazidime-avibactam, meropenem-vaborbactam, imipenem-relebactam, eravacycline, plazomicin, polymyxin (last resort, nephrotoxic) e. **Pseudomonas aeruginosa**: - Intrinsic resistance + acquired - Pip-tazo, cefepime, ceftazidime, meropenem, levofloxacin, aminoglycoside, ceftolozane-tazobactam f. **MDR Acinetobacter**: - Carbapenem-resistant common; very limited; colistin, tigecycline, sulbactam, eravacycline g. **Stenotrophomonas maltophilia**: - TMP-SMX first-line h. **Candida**: - Fluconazole (susceptible — albicans, parapsilosis often) - Echinocandin (caspofungin, micafungin, anidulafungin) — resistant Candida, severe - C. auris emerging multi-drug resistant; (4) **High-risk surgical populations**: prolonged hospitalization, prior antibiotic exposure, ICU, immunosuppressed, transplant, traveled from endemic regions; (5) **Stewardship implementation**: - Antimicrobial Stewardship Program (ASP) — required by Joint Commission + Medicare - Prospective audit + feedback - Formulary restriction + pre-authorization - Education - Surveillance + reporting - Order sets + clinical decision support - De-escalation protocols - IV-to-oral conversion - Allergy delabeling - C. difficile prevention bundles

---

**Antimicrobial stewardship** — central to modern infectious disease + surgical practice. WHO top 10 global health threats includes antimicrobial resistance. Drivers: overuse, misuse, broad-spectrum overreliance, agriculture, lack of new antibiotics. **5 Rs of antibiotic use**: 1. **Right diagnosis** — culture before antibiotic when feasible 2. **Right drug** — narrow when organism known 3. **Right dose** — patient-specific 4. **Right duration** — shortest effective (recent evidence supports shorter courses for many infections; e.g., 5-7 days for uncomplicated pneumonia, abdominal infection if source control adequate) 5. **Right route** — IV-to-oral conversion early when patient stable + absorption adequate **De-escalation** — switch from broad to narrow when sensitivity known. **Source control** — surgical/IR drainage, debridement, device removal — critical; antibiotic alone often inadequate. **Common resistant organisms (priority)**: 1. **ESKAPE** pathogens — common nosocomial multi-drug resistant: - Enterococcus (VRE) - Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) - Klebsiella pneumoniae (ESBL, CRE) - Acinetobacter baumannii (MDR/XDR) - Pseudomonas aeruginosa (MDR) - Enterobacter species 2. **Candida** including auris (emerging MDR) **New antibiotics**: - Ceftolozane-tazobactam (Pseudomonas, ESBL) - Ceftazidime-avibactam (CRE, KPC) - Meropenem-vaborbactam (CRE) - Imipenem-relebactam - Eravacycline (CRE, Acinetobacter) - Cefiderocol — siderophore cephalosporin (CRE, Acinetobacter) - Tedizolid (MRSA, VRE) - Delafloxacin **Stewardship program elements** (CDC core elements): leadership commitment, accountability, drug expertise, action (prospective audit + feedback, formulary), tracking, reporting, education. **MRSA decolonization** (CHG bathing + mupirocin nasal) — reduces SSI + MRSA infections in select surgical populations (cardiac, orthopedic). **Allergy delabeling** — important: > 90% of self-reported penicillin allergies are NOT true IgE allergies; delabeling enables use of effective + narrow first-line agents. **C. difficile prevention**: minimize broad-spectrum + duration; contact precautions; hand hygiene (soap > alcohol for C. diff spores); environmental cleaning.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'Basic science: surgical microbiology — antimicrobial stewardship

คำถาม: antibiotic resistance + stewardship in surgery';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Personal preference only"},{"label":"B","text":"Evidence-Based Surgery — principles + application"},{"label":"C","text":"Ignore patient preferences"},{"label":"D","text":"Use only personal experience"},{"label":"E","text":"No quality measurement needed"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Evidence-Based Surgery — principles + application**: (1) **Hierarchy of evidence** (highest → lowest): - Systematic reviews + meta-analyses of RCTs - RCTs (large, well-designed) - Cohort studies (prospective > retrospective) - Case-control studies - Case series - Case reports - Expert opinion / textbook (NB: hierarchy not absolute — well-conducted observational with large effect > poor RCT); (2) **Surgical evidence challenges**: - RCTs in surgery harder than medical (sham surgery ethics, learning curve, surgeon variability) - Crossover difficult - Equipoise variable - Blinding nearly impossible - Quality variation - Volume + experience effects; (3) **Clinical Practice Guidelines (CPG)** — synthesize evidence: - **GRADE methodology**: assess quality of evidence (high, moderate, low, very low) + strength of recommendation (strong vs conditional/weak) - Major surgical societies: ACS, SAGES, ASCRS, AAST, EAST, WSES, NCCN, SVS, AHPBA, ESC, etc. - International + regional adaptations; (4) **Apply evidence to patient** — EBM cycle: - **Ask** focused clinical question (PICO: Patient, Intervention, Comparison, Outcome) - **Acquire** best evidence - **Appraise** validity + relevance - **Apply** to patient (considering values + circumstances) - **Assess** + reflect on outcomes; (5) **Shared decision-making**: - Patient preferences + values matter - Especially for elective / quality-of-life decisions - Decision aids (Ottawa, Mayo Choice) - Outcomes-focused conversation; (6) **Variation in practice**: - Substantial unwarranted variation in surgical decisions (Dartmouth Atlas) - Quality improvement to reduce variation when evidence clear; (7) **Quality improvement**: - ACS NSQIP — risk-adjusted outcomes benchmark - STS, MBSAQIP, MIPS, others - PDSA cycles, FMEA, RCA - Audit + feedback (Cochrane evidence supports); (8) **Research integration**: - Clinical trial enrollment - Translational research - Implementation science (closing evidence-to-practice gap — Cochrane EPOC); (9) **Critical appraisal**: - Internal validity: bias, confounding, randomization, blinding, ITT analysis - External validity: generalizability to your patient population - Magnitude of effect + clinical relevance - Cost-effectiveness; (10) **Beyond efficacy — patient-reported outcomes (PROs)**: - Quality of life - Functional outcomes - Patient satisfaction - Long-term implications - Capturing what matters to patients

---

**Evidence-Based Surgery** — synthesis of best evidence + clinical expertise + patient values. **Hierarchy of evidence**: meta-analysis > RCT > cohort > case-control > case series > case report > expert opinion. Not absolute — methodologic quality + applicability also matter. **GRADE methodology** (Grading of Recommendations Assessment, Development + Evaluation) — used by WHO + many guidelines: assess quality (high → moderate → low → very low) + strength (strong / conditional) of recommendations. **Surgical research challenges**: - RCT difficult (sham surgery ethics, learning curve, surgeon variability, blinding hard) - Observational + registry data often important - IDEAL framework (Idea → Development → Exploration → Assessment → Long-term study) for surgical innovation evaluation **EBM cycle (PICO + 5 A''s)**: 1. Ask focused question (PICO) 2. Acquire evidence 3. Appraise critically 4. Apply to patient 5. Assess + reflect **Shared decision-making**: - Patient values + preferences part of EBM definition - Decision aids - Especially important: elective, quality-of-life, preference-sensitive conditions (e.g., BPH treatment, prostate cancer, knee replacement, bariatric surgery) **Critical appraisal**: - Internal validity: randomization, allocation concealment, blinding, ITT, attrition - External validity: generalizability - Effect size + confidence interval - NNT (number needed to treat) - Cost-effectiveness **Major guideline organizations**: ACS, SAGES, ASCRS, AAST, EAST, WSES, NCCN, SVS, AHPBA, ESC, ESVS, AHA/ACC, ATS, RCOG, ACOG, AAP. **Quality improvement**: - ACS NSQIP — gold standard for surgical outcomes benchmarking - STS Database (cardiothoracic) - MBSAQIP (bariatric) - MIPS (Medicare quality reporting) - Process measures (SCIP, WHO checklist) - Outcomes measures - Patient-reported outcomes (PROs) **Implementation science**: closing evidence-practice gap — getting proven interventions into routine practice. Cochrane EPOC (Effective Practice + Organization of Care). **Volume-outcome relationship**: higher-volume surgeons + hospitals → better outcomes for complex procedures (Whipple, esophagectomy, hepatectomy, complex cardiac); regionalization of complex surgery debated.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'Basic science: surgical decision-making + evidence-based medicine

คำถาม: evidence-based surgery + clinical practice guidelines';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Avoid all organ donation discussions"},{"label":"B","text":"Organ donation — modern approach"},{"label":"C","text":"Sell organs commercially"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid family input"},{"label":"E","text":"No regulation needed"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Organ donation — modern approach**: (1) **Types of donation**: a. **Deceased donor**: - **Donation after brain death (DBD)** — most common - **Donation after circulatory death (DCD)** — increasing globally - **Tissue donation** — corneas, skin, bone, heart valves — wide donor pool (vs solid organ stricter); b. **Living donor** — kidney (most common), liver lobe, lung lobe, small bowel segment, pancreas segment; (2) **Brain death determination**: - Clinical criteria (irreversible cessation of all brain function): - Cause of coma known + irreversible - Absence of confounders (hypothermia, drugs, metabolic) - Coma without response - Absent brainstem reflexes (pupillary, corneal, vestibulo-ocular, gag, cough) - Apnea test positive (no respiratory drive with PaCO2 > 60) - Confirmatory tests if needed (EEG, cerebral blood flow study, brain death angiogram); (3) **DCD (Donation after Circulatory Death)**: - Donor not brain-dead but has irrecoverable injury + decision to withdraw life support - Withdrawal in OR or ICU; declaration of death after circulatory cessation (5 min asystole typical) - Warm ischemia time minimized for organ recovery - Expanding donor pool — outcomes good in selected (kidney, liver, lung, heart with NRP — normothermic regional perfusion); (4) **Organ procurement organizations (OPO)**: - Coordinate donor evaluation + family approach + organ allocation - Independent from medical team caring for potential donor (separation of duties); (5) **Family approach** — best practice: - Compassionate, after death declaration / family understanding of prognosis - Specialized requesters (OPO coordinators) trained - Right to refuse respected; not coerced - Discuss patient''s wishes (donor card, advance directive, organ donor registry); (6) **Consent**: - Opt-in (most countries — US) — explicit consent required - Opt-out (presumed consent — Spain, Austria, others) — higher donor rates - Family may override registered donor wishes (varies by jurisdiction); (7) **Allocation**: - UNOS / OPTN in US (similar systems globally — Eurotransplant, Australia/NZ ANZDATA, etc.) - Algorithms balance: medical urgency, time on list, blood type/HLA matching, geographic distance, pediatric priority - Special considerations: HCC exception (MELD), Status 1A for fulminant liver failure, etc.; (8) **Living donor**: - Evaluation: medical, psychological, social, financial - Donor advocate / independent assessment - Risks: surgical complications, long-term (kidney function decline modest, but lifelong follow-up needed) - Donor protection — primary goal; (9) **Special situations**: - Anencephalic newborn donation — controversial - Death by neurologic criteria in children - Pregnant donor; (10) **Increase donation**: - Public education + awareness - Family discussions - Donor registry - Required request laws - Routine notification of OPO - Donor management protocols; (11) **Ethics**: separation of donor + recipient care teams, dead donor rule, no payment for organs (with limited exceptions in some countries), pediatric considerations

---

**Organ donation** — central to transplantation; complex ethical, legal, medical framework. **Types**: 1. **Deceased donor**: - DBD (Donation after Brain Death) - most common - DCD (Donation after Circulatory Death) - increasing 2. **Living donor**: kidney (most common), liver lobe, lung lobe, others 3. **Tissue donation**: corneas, skin, bone, heart valves **Brain death** (death by neurologic criteria): - Cause of coma known + irreversible - Confounders excluded (hypothermia, drugs, severe metabolic) - Clinical exam: coma, absent brainstem reflexes, positive apnea test - Confirmatory studies as needed (EEG, cerebral blood flow, angiogram) - Uniform Determination of Death Act (US) + similar laws globally **DCD**: - Maastricht categories I-V (controlled vs uncontrolled) - Withdrawal of life support → asystole → declaration of death (typically 5 min observation) → rapid organ recovery - Warm ischemia time critical for organ viability - Expanding pool — outcomes good for kidney + liver; recently good for heart + lung with NRP (Normothermic Regional Perfusion) **Living donation**: - Kidney most common (~ 30-40% of US transplants) - Liver lobe (right or left lobe — adult-to-adult, left lateral segment adult-to-child) - Donor evaluation comprehensive — medical, psychological, social, financial - Independent donor advocate - Long-term donor follow-up + outcomes tracking - Slight increase in long-term ESRD risk in kidney donors (still low absolute risk) **Ethical principles**: 1. Dead donor rule — vital organs only from confirmed dead 2. Voluntary consent — no coercion, no payment 3. Separation of teams — donor care team independent from recipient/transplant 4. Family approach by OPO + sensitive 5. Equitable allocation 6. Respect for autonomy + patient wishes **Donor management**: aggressive resuscitation post-brain death → optimize organ function for procurement (hemodynamic, hormonal — thyroid, steroid; lung protective ventilation; glycemic control). **OPO + OPTN/UNOS** (US): coordinate, allocate, regulate. **Increasing donation strategies**: opt-out systems (Spain has highest donor rates globally), public education, family discussions, donor registry awareness, required request laws, hospital protocols. **Newer**: extended criteria donor (ECD), hepatitis C+ donor to + recipient with subsequent DAA cure, paired exchange (living kidney swap), domino transplant.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'ระบบ EMS / ethics: organ donation

คำถาม: organ donation + end-of-life';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Burnout not relevant"},{"label":"B","text":"Physician wellness + burnout in surgery — critical professional issue"},{"label":"C","text":"Stigmatize seeking help"},{"label":"D","text":"Single intervention"},{"label":"E","text":"Individual responsibility only"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Physician wellness + burnout in surgery — critical professional issue**: (1) **Definition** (Maslach Burnout Inventory): - Emotional exhaustion - Depersonalization (cynicism toward patients) - Reduced personal accomplishment; (2) **Prevalence**: - Surgeons 40-60% in US studies (varies by specialty + cohort) - General surgeons high; emergency, critical care, oncology elevated - Residents particularly vulnerable; (3) **Consequences**: - Personal: depression, anxiety, substance use, suicide (physicians higher rate than general population), divorce, decreased life satisfaction - Professional: medical errors (~ 2× increased), patient safety, decreased patient satisfaction, decreased empathy, turnover, early retirement, decreased career engagement - Healthcare system: increased costs, decreased quality, workforce shortage; (4) **Drivers**: - System: EHR burden, productivity demands, administrative tasks, regulatory burden, malpractice concerns, RVU pressure, work-hour intensity, on-call burden - Workplace culture: hierarchical, blame culture, lack of autonomy, inadequate teamwork - Individual: maladaptive coping, perfectionism, work-life imbalance, social isolation, financial stress; (5) **Prevention + intervention** — multilevel: a. **Individual strategies**: - Self-care: sleep, exercise, nutrition, hobbies, relationships - Mindfulness, meditation, CBT, professional therapy - Resilience training - Peer support, mentorship - Professional coaching - Setting limits, learning to say no; b. **Organizational/system**: - Reduce administrative burden (scribes, voice recognition) - Improve EHR usability - Wellness officers (Chief Wellness Officer increasing in academic centers) - Schedule design (limit on-call burden, flexible scheduling) - Peer support programs - Mental health services (low barrier, confidentiality protected) - Just culture (vs blame) - Leadership training - Compensation models that don''t solely reward volume; c. **Professional/cultural**: - Destigmatize seeking help - Mental health resources for clinicians (e.g., RISE — Resilience in Stressful Events at Hopkins; Anesthesia Patient Safety Foundation; ACS Surgeon Wellbeing) - Peer support after adverse events (second victim phenomenon) - Bereavement support after patient death - Professional society initiatives; (6) **Surgeon-specific challenges**: - Long training (5-10+ years) - Sleep deprivation - Adverse outcomes psychological impact - Lawsuit risk - Demanding patient care + family demands - Identity tied to work; (7) **Special populations**: - Trainees (high burnout, hidden curriculum exposure) - Women + minority physicians (often face additional stressors — discrimination, harassment, work-family balance) - Mid-career - Late career; (8) **Wellness as patient safety + quality issue** — increasingly recognized; not just individual responsibility; (9) **Mental health crisis among physicians**: - Suicide rate physicians higher than general population (especially female physicians ~ 2× rate) - License restrictions for mental health treatment historically (modernizing — many states now ask only about current impairment vs ever diagnosis - help-seeking should be supported) - Substance use - Depression - Anxiety; (10) **Building wellness culture**: leadership, accountability, measurement (annual surveys), evidence-based interventions, allocate resources, integrate into strategic planning

---

**Physician burnout + wellness** — major contemporary issue in medicine + surgery; recognized as quality + safety issue, not just individual challenge. **Burnout definition** (Maslach): emotional exhaustion + depersonalization + reduced personal accomplishment. **Prevalence in surgery**: 40-60% — highest in general surgery, EM, critical care, oncology; residents particularly vulnerable. **Consequences**: - Personal: depression, anxiety, substance use, divorce, suicide (physicians 2-4× general population, especially female physicians) - Patient: medical errors 2× increased, decreased satisfaction, decreased empathy - Healthcare: turnover, early retirement, costs, workforce shortage **System drivers** (largest factors): - EHR burden + administrative tasks - Productivity demands - Regulatory + malpractice burden - On-call + sleep disruption - Workflow inefficiencies - Inadequate staffing - Culture (hierarchical, blame) **Multilevel intervention**: 1. **Individual**: self-care, mindfulness, CBT, peer support, professional help-seeking, boundary-setting 2. **Organizational/system**: - Reduce EHR + admin burden - Schedule + workload optimization - Wellness officers + programs - Mental health services (confidential, low-barrier) - Peer support programs - Just culture - Leadership training - Recognition + appreciation 3. **Professional/societal**: destigmatize, mental health licensure reform, peer support, professional society initiatives (ACS, AMA, surgical specialty societies) **Second victim phenomenon**: clinicians distressed by patient adverse events — need debriefing, peer support, mental health resources (RISE program Hopkins, etc.). **Mental health licensure**: historically asked about ever diagnosis or treatment → barrier to seeking help; modernizing — questions should focus on current impairment, not history of treatment (American Medical Association advocates; FSMB updated guidance). **Trainee burnout**: very high rates; ACGME duty hour limits, wellness curricula, mental health resources, harassment + mistreatment policies (hidden curriculum exposure significant issue). **Quadruple aim** — original Triple Aim (better care, better health, lower cost) expanded to add clinician wellbeing as essential. **Quality + safety connection**: physician wellbeing correlates with patient outcomes; burnout associated with increased errors, lower patient satisfaction, decreased empathy + adherence to evidence — wellness is patient safety issue. **Special populations** — women, minority, LGBTQ+ physicians often face additional stressors (discrimination, harassment, work-family expectations).'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'EMS: surgical workforce + burnout

คำถาม: physician wellness + burnout in surgery';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Technology not relevant"},{"label":"B","text":"Surgical innovation + emerging technology"},{"label":"C","text":"Avoid all new technology"},{"label":"D","text":"Skip safety evaluation"},{"label":"E","text":"No training needed for new tech"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** **Surgical innovation + emerging technology**: (1) **Robotic surgery** (current state): - **da Vinci** dominant — multiple procedures (urologic, gynecologic, general, cardiac selected, head + neck) - **Versius (CMR), Hugo (Medtronic), Senhance, Stereotaxis** — emerging competitors - Benefits: enhanced visualization (3D), improved ergonomics, articulating instruments, motion scaling, tremor reduction - Disadvantages: cost, training, no haptic feedback, conversion if equipment failure - Best evidence: urology (prostatectomy), gynecology (hysterectomy); growing in colorectal, hepatobiliary, thoracic, cardiac selected; LACC trial showed lap inferior to open for radical hysterectomy cervical cancer — surprising, prompted reconsideration of MIS for cervical Ca; (2) **Imaging + navigation**: - Indocyanine green (ICG) fluorescence — perfusion, lymph node, biliary, tumor margin - 3D reconstruction + virtual reality pre-op planning - Augmented reality intra-op overlay - Hyperspectral imaging - Cone-beam CT intra-op; (3) **Artificial Intelligence + machine learning**: - Image interpretation (pathology, radiology) — FDA-approved AI for some - Surgical decision support - Predictive analytics (risk, complications, recurrence) - Computer vision (intraoperative — phase recognition, instrument tracking, anatomy identification) - Natural language processing (documentation, charting) - Personalized medicine; (4) **Minimally invasive trends**: - Laparoscopic → robotic - Endoscopic procedures (POEM, ESD, EMR, endoscopic anti-reflux, endoscopic bariatric) - NOTES (Natural Orifice Translumenal Endoscopic Surgery) — niche; - Single-incision laparoscopic (SILS) — niche; (5) **Tissue engineering + regenerative medicine**: - Bioprinting (cartilage, skin, vascular grafts experimental; whole organs distant future) - Stem cell therapy (selected — bone, heart in trials) - Decellularized scaffolds (heart valves, vessels, esophagus, trachea) - Mesenchymal stem cells for fistula (darvadstrocel for Crohn''s perianal); (6) **Diagnostics + biomarkers**: - Liquid biopsy (ctDNA) - Precision oncology - Pharmacogenomics; (7) **Telemedicine + telesurgery**: - Pre + post-op virtual visits - Remote second opinion - Tele-trauma consultation - Telementoring (experienced surgeon guides remote surgery) - Telesurgery (true remote surgery — Lindbergh Operation 2001 NY to France; modern: 5G enables; growing in selected countries); (8) **Surgical training innovation**: - Simulation (low + high fidelity, VR) - Video-based assessment (Coaching + feedback) - Crowdsourced surgical assessment - AI-assisted skill evaluation; (9) **Implants + devices**: - 3D-printed patient-specific - Smart implants (sensors, drug-eluting) - Magnetic devices (LINX, anastomosis) - Bioabsorbable - Wireless monitoring; (10) **Ethical + regulatory considerations**: - FDA regulatory (510k vs PMA pathways) - Learning curve + quality outcomes - Data privacy + cybersecurity - Equity + access (technology gap) - Cost-effectiveness - Informed consent for novel - Conflict of interest disclosure - IDEAL framework for surgical innovation evaluation (Stages 1-5: Idea, Development, Exploration, Assessment, Long-term study)

---

**Surgical innovation + emerging technology** — rapid evolution; balance enthusiasm with rigorous evaluation. **Robotic surgery**: - da Vinci dominant; new competitors entering market - Strong evidence in urology (prostatectomy), gynecology (hysterectomy) - Growing in colorectal, hepatobiliary, thoracic - LACC trial NEJM 2018 — surprising: laparoscopic radical hysterectomy for cervical cancer INFERIOR to open for OS + recurrence; prompted reconsideration of MIS in cervical Ca + cautioned ''MIS always better'' assumption - Cost-effectiveness debated for many indications **AI + machine learning in surgery**: - Image interpretation (pathology — Paige.AI, others; radiology — many FDA-cleared) - Surgical decision support, risk prediction - Computer vision intraoperative (phase recognition, instrument tracking, anatomy ID — Cas Squared, Theator, others) - Clinical decision support - Documentation NLP (Nuance DAX, Augmedix) **Imaging adjuncts**: - **ICG fluorescence** — practical, expanding: perfusion (anastomosis, flap), lymph node mapping (sentinel), biliary visualization, tumor margins, parathyroid identification - **Augmented reality** — pre-op planning + intraoperative overlay - **3D printing** — patient-specific implants, anatomical models for planning **Minimally invasive evolution**: - Laparoscopic → robotic for many - Endoscopic procedures expanding (POEM achalasia, ESD early Ca, endoscopic anti-reflux, endoscopic bariatric — sleeve gastroplasty + others) **Tissue engineering**: - Bioprinting still early - Decellularized scaffolds (heart valves, vessels — TAVR + TAVI growing) - Stem cell + regenerative — selected applications (mesenchymal stem cells for Crohn''s fistula — darvadstrocel; others) **Telesurgery**: - Lindbergh Operation 2001 (proof-of-concept) - 5G + low latency enabling near-real-time - Currently telementoring + tele-consultation widespread; true telesurgery limited but growing **Innovation evaluation framework** — IDEAL Collaboration (Stages 1-5: Idea → Development → Exploration → Assessment → Long-term Study) — analog to drug Phase I-IV; structured approach to surgical innovation evaluation; rigorous + safe vs unevaluated adoption. **FDA regulation**: 510(k) clearance (substantial equivalence) vs PMA (premarket approval — higher risk devices); De Novo for novel low/moderate risk; debates about appropriate rigor + post-market surveillance. **Equity + access**: cost + technology gaps concern; rural + LMIC populations may not benefit equally. **Privacy + cybersecurity** — increasingly important with connected devices + data.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'surgery'
  and scenario = 'EMS / quality: telesurgery + technology

คำถาม: surgical innovation + emerging technology';

commit;
